<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Albania Sign Protocol to Fight Border Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Albania signed here
Monday a protocol to strengthen the two countries' cooperation in
combating the increasing border crimes.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, signed by Greek Merchant Marine Minister Stavros
Soumakis and Albanian Interior Minister Neritan Ceka who is
accompanying President Rexhep Mejdani to visit Greece, provides
for joint patrols by the border police and Greek harbour police
corps for the more effective policing of the two countries' sea
borders.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries are expected to sign an
educational cooperation agreement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the cooperation protocol came after Mejdani
discussed with his Greek counterpart Costis Stephanopoulos the
rights of 300,000 ethnic Greeks living in southern Albania and the
growing tension in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, where ethnic
Albanians comprise 90 percent of the nearly two million
population.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, both sides stressed the need of broadening
their relations in all sectors and of seeking peaceful solution to
the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
Mejdani promised that his country would respect the ethnic
Greek minority's rights in accordance with international
standards.
</P>
<P>
For Greece, it allowed last year a large number of Albanian
illegal immigrants to register and work there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
