<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Donates 50,000 Tons of Grain to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korea announced Monday that it
will donate 50,000 tons of grain, worth about 10 million
U.S. dollars, to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in response to the World Food Program's
appeal for food aid of 378.2 million dollars this year to the
DPRK, which has suffered food shortages because of droughts and
floods in past years.
</P>
<P>
Seoul had extended 5.2 million dollars to the DPRK last year
out of its promised 10 million dollars' aid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South Korean National Red Cross is expected to
propose this week inter-Korean Red Cross talks to discuss food
donations by the private sector, whose provision of grain could
amount to 50,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Minister of National Unification Kang In-duck said Monday that
Seoul will continue to donate aid to the DPRK through the Red
Cross and international relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
But with government-to-government food aid, massive aid would
have to be preceded by inter-Korean talks, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
