<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Begins Inquiry into Cause of Mad Cow Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain began to investigate the
causes of mad cow disease on Monday, one of the worst public
health scandals in the country.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister jack Cunningham ordered Lord Justice
Nicholas Phillips to head the inquiry into mad cow disease, or
bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE).
</P>
<P>
Phillips has promised that there will be no witch-hunt and that
the aim is not to find fault, but to see what can be learned from
previous errors.
</P>
<P>
"This is an extremely important inquiry. Many people have been
affected, some tragically, by BSE and Creutzfeld-Jakob Disease
(CJD, the human equivalent). I hope this inquiry will reveal
events and decisions which led to the spread of these diseases,"
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
But he said he would also ask Prime Minister Tony Blair for an
extra six months to consider the evidence. The inquiry is
currently due to report by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The first case of BSE was found in November 1986 but the
British government did not officially announce BSE's existense
until March 1996. So far 24 cases of new-strain CJD have been
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The costs of the investigation, including a website which will
carry daily transcripts and witnesses' submissions, are estimated
at 10 million pounds (16 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
