<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary to Visit Egypt Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 9 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
is due here on March 15 on a visit to forge closer links with
Egypt, the Middle East News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cook's three-day stay in Egypt falls within a tour of the
region aimed at projecting a bigger British profile in the
Arab countries as the current chairman of the rotating EU
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Britain and these states already
exceeded 12 billion sterlings (20.04 billion U.S. dollars) last
year.
</P>
<P>
Cook will arrange and set an exact date for the visit by
British Prime Minister Tony Blair to the Mideast next month, a
move seemingly designed to plaster over the fault line perceived
in London's relations with Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Hot on the heels of the Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms inspection,
Britain and the U.S. have been much criticized throughout the Arab
world for applying double-standard approach to issues of the
region.
</P>
<P>
Britain's resolve to vitalize its relations with Arabs
manifests itself in the speech delivered by Cook in London
recently before a meeting of the Arab-British Friendship
Society.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, he stressed Britain's unshakable desire to
cultivate an Arab-British partnership, particularly in light of
the deeply-rooted relations between the two sides and the
strategic importance of the Middle East region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
