<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Urged to Help End Kosovo Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Albanian President Rexhep
Mejdani on Monday urged neighboring Greece to help defuse the
growing tension in Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The tension in Kosovo would pose "a serious threat" to peace in
the Balkan region, Mejdani said after meeting his Greek
counterpart, Costis Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
He added that Greece, as a member of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU), should play its
role in helping to seek a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mejdani, who arrived here Monday for three days, was on his
first official visit to Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece has reiterated that the Kosovo issue should be resolved
through dialogue, with respect for the rights of ethnic Albanians
and the unity and sovereignty of the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
In January, Greece offered to host a meeting between Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, the leader of the ethnic Albanians,
Ibrahim Rugova, and Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano to help
settle their problems.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo was an autonomous province that formed part of Serbia
until 1989 when Serbian authorities revoked the autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Violence in Kosovo has been growing this year following the
non-implementation of an education agreement reached between
Milosevic and Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
Tension heightened there after a Serbian police patrol and
local ethnic Albanians engaged in fierce cross-fire that killed
four policemen and 16 Albanians on February 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
