<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural NPC Deputies on Agricultural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Five deputies to the on-going
Ninth National People's Congress gave a general picture of China's
rural economic growth and grass-roots work at a press conference
held here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Junxian, a Communist Party secretary in Nongan County, a
grain producer in northeast China's Jilin Province, said his
county has reaped good grain harvests for years thanks to Party's
rural policies and favorable geological conditions there.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, he said, the county earned 5.5 billion yuan (663
million US dollars) from agricultural production, 20.1 times the
figure for 1978, and reaped in 1.97 million tons of grain, 3.8
times the 1978 figure. Farmers' per-capita annual income rose to
2,600 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jianzhi, a Party secretary from a mountainous area in
Shandong Province, said local people have become no longer needy
by growing vegetable, which have been sold to 29 Chinese provinces
and six countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local farmers elected a village managing committee
which serve them wholeheartedly.
</P>
<P>
He Qiongying, a municipal Party secretary from east China's
Shandong Province, said it is essential to implement to the letter
the state's relevant policies on easing the farmers' burden, and
that anyone who violates the policies will be punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Lawmakers Have Unanimous Views on Major Issues (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese lawmakers attending the
first session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC),
China's top legislature, have shown astonishing unanimity in their
views on a series of major issues concerning the country's past
and future development in the session's first stage.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five days, nearly 3,000 NPC deputies from 34
delegations have examined a government work report by incumbent
Premier Li Peng, China's draft development plan and budgets for
1998 and a bold government restructuring plan submitted by the
State Council, the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Since this NPC session will elect a new central
government, lawmakers have mainly focused their attention on the
accomplishments of the current government and relevant experience
in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
While sharing a feeling of satisfaction about China's
achievements in the past five years, they generally agreed to Li's
summarization of the experience for these years' development,
which they said will provide significant guidance for China's
future development.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts describe the current NPC session as another
major attempt of the country since the 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) last September to
comprehensively review its development path and experience.
</P>
<P>
They note that since the session will translate the guidelines
of the 15th CPC National Congress into a state will, it's of
great significance to the attainment of China's development goals
at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Many lawmakers noted that after two decades of reforms and
opening to the outside world, top Chinese decision-makers have
gained more accurate knowledge of China's national conditions, and
have handled complicated relations between reforms, development
and stability fairly well.
</P>
<P>
The ability of China's collective central leadership to
maintain an excellent command of the overall situation under
complicated circumstances is a key factor for all successes of the
past years, and also a reliable guarantee for the country's future
development, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Lawmakers Have Unanimous Views on Major Issues (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In their group discussions, legislators also voiced their
approval for targets and tasks for China's economic and social
development this year put forth by the premier in his report.
</P>
<P>
Most of them believe that the goal of an eight percent economic
growth is realistic and attainable, but not easy to reach.
</P>
<P>
Under the impact of the financial crisis in Southeast Asia, a
practical option for the Chinese government in its attempt to
stimulate economic growth is to expand domestic demand through an
appropriate increase of investment, the lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
However, they suggested that the government should continue to
maintain a relatively-tight fiscal and monetary policy, pay
special attention to the prevention of redundant construction, and
inject the bulk of its investment in key sectors like
communications, environmental protection, infrastructure
development, industries supported by high and new technologies,
and housing.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers also noted that with reforms, especially the
reform of state-owned enterprises, entering a critical stage, it's
very important for the government to cautiously handle various
social conflicts and strive to eliminate hidden dangers in the
national economy, particularly in the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that a major characteristic of the current NPC
session, convened at a time when profound changes are taking place
in China's economic and social structures, is that both senior
officials and lawmakers from grassroots units have shown greater
concerns about the interests of the general public.
</P>
<P>
They noted that issues like re-employment of laid-off workers
and reducing farmers' economic burdens have been frequently
mentioned in speeches of central government leaders during their
panel discussions with local delegations of NPC deputies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Lawmakers Have Unanimous Views on Major Issues (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The State Council plan of institutional restructuring has
become another major topic in the legislators' discussions these
days.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers have used words like "long-expected",
"inevitable", "practical" and "realistic" to express their
appreciation of this plan, which will kick off the largest
government reform since the founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
They generally believe that this plan, which has responded to
the urgent need of a socialist market economic system, will be
approved by the current NPC session without any difficulty.
</P>
<P>
But they expressed the hope that the plan, once adopted, would
be carried out earnestly and smoothly to ensure a success.
</P>
<P>
Most legislators pointed out that the "bottleneck" for China's
state enterprise reform at present is the re-employment of
laid-off workers and an early establishment of a social security
system.
</P>
<P>
They said that once these difficulties are overcome, reform of
state enterprises can be pushed forward smoothly.
</P>
<P>
There are also quite a few lawmakers who stressed the
importance of sustainable development and raised proposals on the
protection of the environment and resources.
</P>
<P>
Starting tomorrow afternoon, the NPC session will enter its
second phase, when deputies will focus on hearing and examining
work reports by the NPC Standing Committee, the Supreme People's
Court and the Supreme People's Procuratorate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
