<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Firms Liquidated in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A total of 132 companies in
different sectors of the economy in Zimbabwe have either been
liquidated, placed under judicial management or declared
insolvent during the past 14 months due to a harsh economic
climate, a business information and service provider said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Dun and Bradstreet Company, Fernando
Aleixo told the Zimbabwe News Agency that last year alone, 92
firms were liquidated, eight placed under judicial management and
16 declared insolvent.
</P>
<P>
Aleixo said that this year 14 companies have been liquidated
and two declared insolvent.
</P>
<P>
The sectors most affected were clothing, engineering,
hospitality, construction, manufacturing, and trade and commerce
which had seen 83 companies collapsing, leaving thousands of
people without jobs.
</P>
<P>
" The general business outlook for 1998 is not good, we expect
more companies to liquidate than in 1997,'' Aleixo said.
</P>
<P>
''The reasons why companies are liquidating are high interest
rates, depreciation of the Zimbabwean Dollar, inflation, bad
management and competition.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
