<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Beef Consumption Increases by 9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The British people have gained more
confidence on their own beef by consuming nine percent more beef
than last year, according to a government report published on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report, issued by the Agriculture Ministry's National Food
Survey, said the increase, to 110 grams per person a week, showed
it was back in line with the declining long-term tread.
</P>
<P>
The amount of beef eaten by Britons has been in decline for
more than a decade, and in 1996 the consumption plunged by 17
percent compared to the previous year after the government warned
that bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) could be transmitted
to humans in the form of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD).
</P>
<P>
So far, 23 Britons have contracted the new form of CJD which
scientists studying mad cow disease have identified.
</P>
<P>
British exports of beef have been banned by the European Union
for almost two years, dealing a heavy blow to British beef
industry and cow breeding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two More Banks Increase Lending Rates in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Two more commercial banks in
Zimbabwe Monday announced increases in minimum lending rates as a
result of the prevailing market conditions and tight money market
rates.
</P>
<P>
The increases in lending rates by 1.5 percent to 35 percent by
First Banking Corporation and Barclays Bank Zimbabwe follows the
same move by Standard Chartered and Stanbic last week as
instability that has been gripping the money market since the end
of 1997 continues, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Our minimum lending rate has been increased by 1.5 percent to
35 percent per annum with effect from March 1, 1998. Deposits
rates have also been adjusted," said First Banking Corporation in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, "The rate increase is in response to
prevailing market conditions and reflects a general tightening in
money market rates."
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks last hiked minimum lending rates by three
percentage points to 33.5 percent last December following a three
percentage point increase in the rediscount rate by the Reserve
Bank of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the hikes in lending rates to the current
high cost of money on the market caused by the shortage of cash
created by the Central Bank to control money supply growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
