<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Determined to Revamp Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Minister for Tourism Henry
Kesgey has said that the government had made great efforts to
ensure tourists' security in a bid to revamp the country's
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Sunday when he met with the
Secretary-General of the World Tourism Organization (WTO),
Francesco Frangialli in Berlin, Germany, the Kenya News Agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that effective machinery had been put in
place to enhance the security of tourists visiting the East
African country.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the recent murder of a British tourist in
Kenya was an isolated and unfortunate criminal act which was
being pursued in the court of law.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kenyan government was urgently addressing the
extensive road damages caused by the El Nino phenomenon over the
past four months.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, WTO secretary-general lauded the efforts made
by the Kenyan government to enhance tourists security in the
country and noted that security was the key to successful tourism
promotion campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan minister is on a tour to European countries
including Germany, Italy, France, Britain and Sweden to market
Kenya as one of Africa's best destinations for tourists.
</P>
<P>
Kosegey said late last month that his ministry would
aggressively market Kenya and improve its image abroad in the
world, especially in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's tourism, the country's number one foreign exchange
earner, is undergoing "the worst times since independence in
1963" with tourists visiting the country decreasing from 850,000
in 1994 to about 600,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attributed the decline of the country's tourism
mainly to the uncollected rubbish everywhere, badly damaged
roads, insecurity and violence, and water and power shortages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
