<HEADLINE> Sitaram Kesri Resigns as Congress President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 9 (Xinhua) -- In a dramatic development,
Congress President Sitaram Kesri Monday announced his decision to
resign as the Congress president.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, he said that he had taken
the step in view of the developments in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
"Have you not seen how things took shape during the last two
months? No man with self-respect could tolerate this," he said.
</P>
<P>
The last two months has seen frequent references by the party's
star campaigner and widow of former Prime Minister Sonia Gandhi
that the party "needed a right leadership to make it strong and
vibrant."
</P>
<P>
Kesri made a veiled attack on Sonia Gandhi at the press
conference, but he did not elaborate on it.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would convene a meeting of the Congress Working
Committee (CWC), the highest policy-making body of the party,
Tuesday to decide the date for the election of the Congress
Parliamentary Party (CPP).
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that he was not a candidate for the CPP
leadership.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some Congress leaders welcomed Sitaram Kesri's
decision to resign as the party president.
</P>
<P>
It was definitely good for the future of the party. It was also
a clear indication that he wanted to hand over the reins of the
party to the "younger generation", said party senior leader Sharad
Pawar.
</P>
<P>
Kesri's decision to quit showed that Congress leaders can
always rise to the occasion, said another senior party leader G.
Nabi Azad.
</P>
<P>
It was time for Sonia Gandhi to take over the presidentship of
the Congress, party leader G. Vyas said.
</P>
<P>
83-year-old Kesri was elected the Congress President on June 9
last year following the resignation of P. V. Narasimha Rao.
</P>
</TEXT>
