<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Inputs $10m into Poverty Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The South African government has
allocated 50 million Rand (about 10 million U.S. dollars) to poverty
relief projects countrywide, the welfare authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Welfare Minister Geraldine Fraser-Moleketi handed out the checks,
part of the special anti-poverty fund announced by the Finance
Ministry last year, to 1,139 projects across the country at a ceremony
in Cape Town Monday, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The checks had been issued directly to the projects instead of
provincial coffers to ensure that within a few days the money would be
in the hands of those projects, Fraser-Moleketi said.
</P>
<P>
The projects would target women and poor communities, especially in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the South African population live below the 301-Rand
(61 dollar) poverty line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
