<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier on Exploring Rural Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Li Lanqing, vice-premier of the
State Council, stressed the importance of exploring the rural
market to expand sales of consumer and capital goods as well as to
meet the need of farmers.
</P>
<P>
In a group discussion attended by deputies to the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC),in session here since last
Thursday, he said that, while there are huge amounts of surplus
goods held in stock in cities, farmers in the vast countryside do
not have easy access to markets and, when they do have access to
markets, often very few varieties of goods are available there.
</P>
<P>
Neither manufacturing departments nor sales outlets have paid
enough attention to exploring the rural market, said Li, who is
also Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of the
Communist Party of China Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Inexpensive goods sell well in the countryside as long as they
meet farmers' needs, and manufacturers of such goods can have good
economic returns, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Modern commercial businesses including chain stores should
also establish their presence in the vast countryside," he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier also urged accelerated development of markets
for second-hand goods in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Says No Decision on Re-entry to Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A Sinn Fein leader said Monday his
party would not decide whether to return to the Northern Ireland
peace talks until after a meeting later this week with Prime
Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
Irish Republic Army(IRA), said at a press conference in Belfast
that "Mr Blair has agreed to meet Sinn Fein. As soon as that
meeting takes place and we have had the opportunity to express our
concerns... then Sinn Fein will be in a position to judge how and
when we re-enter the talks process."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein was suspended from the talks two weeks ago until
Monday because of the alleged involvement of IRA guerrillas in two
killings in Northern Ireland last month.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has requested such a meeting with Blair on the crisis
and the Downing Street has expressed readiness to meet with Adams
later this week.
</P>
<P>
Adams said the damage the suspension had done to confidence in
the talks process was being underestimated, according to BBC
report.
</P>
<P>
The other political parties in the peace talks resumed
negotiations in Belfast on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The British and Irish governments have set a deadline in May
for the parties to come up with a settlement in the dispute over
British rule of Northern Ireland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
