<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament in Hot Debate on Removing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Following heated debate,
Israeli Knesset (Parliament) Monday demanded Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai to decide whether to remove the gravesite of
Baruch Goldstein, who massacred 29 Muslims four years ago in
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Temper flared at the meeting of the Knesset Interior Committee
as leftwing and righwing lawmakers differed sharply over the issue
of removing Goldstein's tomb in the Kiryat Arba settlement
adjacent Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Jewish extremist Goldstein gunned down 29 Muslim prayers
inside the Tomb of Patriarchs (Ibrahim Mosque called by Arabs)
in February, 1994. He was killed by other Muslim prayers and
late buried in Kiryat Arba. His gravesite has since been
turned into a pilgrim site for Jewish extremists, who provoked
the Arab anger by holding memorials at the site every year.
</P>
<P>
Israeli peace movement Peace Now and leftist politicians have
been calling for the removal of Goldstein's tomb from Kiryat
Arba, a move strongly opposed by Jewish settlers and rightwing
politicians.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leftist party Meretz's lawmaker Ran Cohen has
tabled a bill to the Knesset demanding for the relocation of
Goldstein's gravesite. At the meeting, Cohen said it is a
disgrace to the State of Israel that Goldstein's gravesite
remains there ever since the Hebron Massacre.
</P>
<P>
Communist Hadash Party's lawmaker Ahmed Saad also came out in
support to Cohen's position, saying that Goldstein's gravesite
should be removed to a new garbage dump in the Negev desert.
</P>
<P>
But Benny Elon, of the extremist rightwing Moledet Party,
counter-charged the leftist politicians for exploiting the issue
to attempt to uproot the Jewish communities in Hebron and Kiryat
Arba. But even he admitted that Goldstein was a murderer whose
tomb should not be turned into a pilgrim place.
</P>
<P>
Shmuel Halpert, lawmaker of the the rightwing religious party
United Torah Judaism, joined Elon in opposing the removal of
Goldstein's gravesite citing the Jewish religious laws.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Salah Tarif, of the opposition Labor Party,
finally ruled that the issue would be handed over to the defense
minister to decide by the end of next week the fate of Goldstein's
tomb. Tarif himself also believed that Goldstein's tomb must be
removed to bring an end to the lingering controversy over the
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0034 </DOCNO>
