<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Firm Sees IT Market Growth in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. information
technology media company predicted that China's IT market may
reach 21.5 billion U.S. dollars by 2002 from 7.3 billion dollars
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In its recent forecast the Boston-based International Data
Group (IDG) set the 1997-2001 compound annual growth rate of
Internet users in China at 73 percent, IDG said in a press release
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
IDG sees an increase of its presence in the Asia Pacific region
with the recent launch of the monthly magazine Internetworld in
China.
</P>
<P>
The publication informs an audience of 50,000 readers about new
trends and technologies in the networking market, industry events,
and the effects of the Internet on Chinese economics and society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Firm Sees IT Market Growth in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. information
technology media company predicted that China's IT market may
reach 21.5 billion U.S. dollars by 2002 from 7.3 billion dollars
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In its recent forecast the Boston-based International Data
Group (IDG) set the 1997-2001 compound annual growth rate of
Internet users in China at 73 percent, IDG said in a press release
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
IDG sees an increase of its presence in the Asia Pacific region
with the recent launch of the monthly magazine Internetworld in
China.
</P>
<P>
The publication informs an audience of 50,000 readers about new
trends and technologies in the networking market, industry events,
and the effects of the Internet on Chinese economics and society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Urges Governments to Stop Sending Asylum-Seekers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) has urged European governments to stop sending
rejected asylum-seekers from Kosovo back to the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR statement released here on Monday came in the wake of an
upsurge in violence in Kosovo which left dozens of people dead.
</P>
<P>
"Given the current situation in Kosovo, UNHCR urges governments to
suspend the return of rejected asylum-seekers from Kosovo on
humanitarian grounds," said Dennis McNamara, UNHCR's Director of
International Protection.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo Albanians whose asylum applications have been rejected
should not be sent back until the situation in the province returns to
stability, UNHCR said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
European countries have regularly returned rejected asylum-seekers
to Yugoslavia, according to UNHCR. The overwhelming majority of
asylum-seekers from Yugoslavia are ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Until now, UNHCR has not objected to Kosovo Albanians being sent
back, as long as their asylum claims have been thoroughly reviewed.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR estimates that there are currently more than 150,000 people,
mostly Kosovo Albanians, who are in line for return, based on
bilateral agreements between countries of asylum and Belgrade
authorities.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, UNHCR expressed alarm about the recent upsurge in
violence in Kosovo, urging all concerned to make every effort to
prevent a further escalation which could trigger new waves of
refugees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-09 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges to Advance Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH (WEST BANK), March 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Jordanian
Crown Prince Hassan Ibn Talal Monday called on both Israeli and
Palestinian leaders to advance the peace talks as the
Iraqi-U.N. crisis over arms inspection has been resolved.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat in the West Bank city of Ramallah, Hassan
told reporters that since so much have been achieved in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, it is important for both sides
to continue it.
</P>
<P>
He said the peaceful resolution of the Iraqi crisis indicates
that the Israeli-Palestinian dispute could also be settled under
the auspices of the international community.
</P>
<P>
Hassan stressed that the related parties should act in
accordance with the international legitimacy and implement the
signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that the agreement signed with Israel is not a
bilateral agreement, but an international agreement, calling on
the international community to make further efforts to advance the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been deadlocked for a
year. The Palestinians have repeatedly accused Israel of
deliberately hindering the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel is insisting that the pullback from the West
Bank, a key factor in the peace process, was contingent on the
implementation of the Palestinian commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that obstacles do remain in the negotiations with
Israel, but it is important to overcome the obstacles and keep the
stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
Hassan's trip in the Palestinian self-rule area came after
Israeli National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon's visit to
Amman Sunday night, which improved the strained relations between
Israel and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The relations were strained by a failed assassination attempt
by two agents of Israeli secret service Mossad of a Hamas (Islamic
Resistance Movement) leader in Amman last September.
</P>
<P>
Hassan will also meet with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Tuesday in Tel-Aviv to discuss ways of pushing forward
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
