<HEADLINE> Britain Expects Good Results From `98 Yonex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, ENGLAND, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain does not have
any of its players in seeded positions at `98 Yonex All England
Championships, but they are still expected to do well.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the first day of the Championships, Asger Madsen,
England National Coach, said: "Our players have prepared well for
the Championships. They have been training hard and I expect this
effort to be reflected in their performance."
</P>
<P>
There would be some hard matches but "I want to see good
results from our players", he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the draw for the Championships, England's top
men's singles players, Darren Hall and Peter Knowles are placed in
the bottom half of the draw with No.2 seed Sun Jun from China.
</P>
<P>
Peter Gade Christensen from Denmark takes the No.1 position and
the 1997 Winner Dong Jiong from China is seeded 3/4 in the top
half.
</P>
<P>
English National Champion Julia Mann is drawn in the top half
where China's Gong Zhichao is seeded 1. Ye Zhaoying, the 1997
Yonex All England Champion from China, is seeded 2 and shares the
bottom half of the ladies' singles draw with England's Rebecca
Pantaney, Jo Muggeridge and Justine Willmott.
</P>
<P>
Simon Archer and Chris Hunt, England's top men's doubles pair
have been placed in the top half of the draw where Cheah Soon Kit
and Yap Kim Hock are at No.1.
</P>
<P>
1997 mixed doubles semi finalists Chris Hunt and Donna Kellogg
are placed in the bottom half along with the 1997 mixed doubles
winners Liu Yong and Ge Fei from China.
</P>
<P>
Hunt and Kellogg were beaten 15-6 and 15-4 by Liu Yong and Ge
Gei in last year's semi final. However, both of them are looking
forward to the chance to "even the score" this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
