<HEADLINE> U.N. to Police S. Lebanon If Israelis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. peacekeeping forces are
ready to carry out their due responsibilities in south Lebanon if
Israel withdraws from the region, the forces' spokesman said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Timor Goksel, spokesman of the 5,400-strong U.N. Interim Force
in South Lebanon (UNIFIL), made the remarks when meeting with the
southern commander of Hezbollah resistance movement Sheikh Nabil
Kawou.
</P>
<P>
Goksel said that the U.N. forces have not been officially
informed about the Israeli conditional offer to pull out from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said that it is willing to withdraw from south
Lebanon if the Lebanese government agrees its security
arrangements, including disarming Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, backed by Iran, has been spearheading the
guerrilla's resistance against Israeli occupation of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its northern areas from
cross-border Lebanese guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Kawou said that Israel wants to avoid further losses and is not
interested in withdrawing from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that his party will continue to fight the Israeli
occupying forces, adding that the resistance movement will not be
affected by the Israeli maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The UNIFIL was established in March 1978 after Israeli first
invasion of Lebanon. But the forces have been unable to fulfill its
mission of bringing peace to southern Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-09 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Ready to Meet Turkish Cypriot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
is willing to meet Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash if
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan extends an invitation to the
leaders of the two communities in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides was speaking to
reporters here Monday after a meeting between Clerides and
visiting U.S. State Department Cyprus Coordinator Tom Miller.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said the Cypriot government is prepared to discuss
the substance of the Cyprus problem in order to reach a
comprehensive solution.
</P>
<P>
"We have the good will to work toward a settlement with
determination and seriousness," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides disclosed that Miller reiterated the
U.S. administration's determination to step up its efforts to
settle the Cyprus question within the framework of the
U.N. initiative.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cypriot government's decision to purchase the
Russian-made surface-to-air missile system S-300 was brought up
at the meeting between Clerides and Miller.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it is now understood that the S-300s are part and
parcel of the substance of the Cyprus question and the Republic's
security.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed an agreement to purchase the S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles from Russia early last year, and the missiles are due to
arrive on the island later this year.
</P>
<P>
The decision was criticized by the U.S. and some other western
countries, and Turkey has threatened to strike the missiles if
they are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
But the Cypriot government has reiterated that the deal could
be canceled if President Clerides' proposal for demilitarization
of the island is realized, or the bicommunal peace talks make
progress.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said that ways to overcome obstacles in efforts to
solve the Cyprus problem were also discussed at the
meeting. "There are many ways to back the U.N. efforts," he added.
</P>
<P>
The two Cypriot communities' leaders held two rounds of
U.N.-sponsored peace talks last summer, which ended in failure due
to Denktash's refusal for further talks because of the European
Union (EU)'s decision to start accession negotiations with the
Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Last week Denktash sent a letter to Clerides in which he
essentially rejected an agreement between the two sides, which was
reached over 20 years ago, to establish a federation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated his long-standing demand for recognition of
his breakaway Republic unilaterally established in 1983 in
northern Cyprus, which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Clerides returned the letter as it was totally unacceptable in
terms of substance and ethics.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contact Group Urges Political Dialogue on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the Contact
Group on former Yugoslavia ended the one-day emergency meeting on
Kosovo here Monday, calling on the Yugoslav government and ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo to resolve their disputes through peaceful
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after the meeting, British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook condemned both the Serbian security
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army for their violent actions,
which have killed at least 80 people.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon the authorities in Belgrade to investigate the
very serious allegations of extrajudicial killings. If these
accusations are borne out we expect the Yugoslav government to
punish those responsible," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Under the final statement of the meeting, the Contact Group,
comprising the United States, Russia, Britain, France, Germany and
Italy, adopted the following punishment measures:
</P>
<P>
-- request the U.N. Security Council to consider "a
comprehensive arms embargo" against both the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia (FRY) and its Kosovo region;
</P>
<P>
-- refusal to supply equipment to the FRY which might be used
for internal repression;
</P>
<P>
-- Denial of visas for Senior FRY government officials
responsible for repression actions in Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
-- Moratorium on government financed credit support for trade
and investment.
</P>
<P>
However, the Russian delegation at first rejected all the
suggestions, but later agreed to accept the first two measures
after Cook having an urgent telephone conversation with Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who did not attend the London
meeting himself.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group ministers, which have decided to meet again
on March 25 to assess the response of the Yugoslav government,
also requested the United Nations High Commissioner for Human
Rights and the Organization for Security and Cooperation on Europe
to send separate missions to the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
