<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Leaves for Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides left here Monday for Athens for talks with Greek Premier
Costas Simitis on the Cyprus problem and Cyprus' accession course
toward European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Clerides told reporters here that he
leaves for Athens at the invitation of the Greek premier to
exchange views on some issues.
</P>
<P>
"During our discussions, we shall exchange views on the
substance of the Cyprus problem as well as on our accession
course," he added.
</P>
<P>
He explained that "all matters pertaining to these two issues
will be discussed."
</P>
<P>
However, he said defense issues will not be on the agenda of
his talks in the Greek capital. Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou
will go to Athens to deal with these issues, he added.
</P>
<P>
This is Clerides' first visit to Athens since he was re-elected
in February's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Clerides will fly to London to participate in the European
Conference on March 12, after his talks in Athens. Fifteen EU
member-states and 11 applicant countries will participate in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The EU summit last December decided to start accession talks
with Cyprus on March 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> About 5.3 Percent of Zambians Under 13 Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A Zambian senior official revealed
here Monday that about 5.3 percent of Zambians by the age of 13 years
are regular smokers, Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Chairing a national conference on tobacco or health, Nelson
Magolo, Deputy Permanent Secretary at the Ministry of Health,
said that studies show that 39 percent of Zambian men smoke
cigarettes while seven percent of women smoke.
</P>
<P>
And the consumption among the youth is alarming and has extended
to substances like industrial glue, aviation oil, petrol and bio-gas
from sewage, according to Magolo.
</P>
<P>
The effect of smoking on the young, said Magolo, include
addiction, lung diseases, cancer and low intellectual development
which reduces them to resistance to infection.
</P>
<P>
Magolo lamented that the cost to health care and
family looking after chronically ill patients is overburdening to a
developing country like Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has no explict policy on tobacco, it has
made available legislation to control tobacco use in the country,
said Magolo.
</P>
<P>
Zambia enacted a statutory instrument in 1992 which compels
tobacco manufacturers to label cigarette packets with a health
warning and stipulates that smoking in public places is banned and
sale of cigarettes to children is restricted.
</P>
<P>
The law also restricts cigarettes advertising in both electronic
and print media, said Magolo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Set up Soup Kitchens in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food Program
(WFP) will set up soup kitchens in war-ravaged Sierra Leone to feed
the neediest people, a report reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Conakry at the weekend, WFP Representative Patrick
uckley said an initial 5,000 - 6000 people have been targeted as the
most needy, but added that the situation around the southern and eastern
towns of Bo and Kenema remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
The soup kitchens will be set over the next few weeks in capital
Freetown, with some food-for-work schemes, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Buckley admitted that a general distribution of food is widely
expected, but said the WFP will not do that.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he said WFP expects the shortage of food for the general
public to be solved by commercial supplies, which will resume as
normalcy returns.
</P>
<P>
The first shipment of aid food arrived in Freetown in mid-February,
when the West Africa peace-keeping force ECOMOG drove the military
junta of Johnny Koromah out from capital.
</P>
<P>
Buckley said food shipment will now spread to the interior and will
continue for at least three months, he said.
</P>
<P>
Complaining that "security is still the main problem", Buckley said
a U.N. team would travel to Bo to assess the security situation there.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's elected president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who has been
in exile in Guinea since being ousted by Koromah's coup last May, will
return to Freetown Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
