<HEADLINE> Iran, Belarus Sign 4 Documents on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Belarus Monday signed four
letters of understanding and a joint communique at the end of the
official visit of Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko to
Tehran, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Without elaborating the letters of understanding, the report
said that the two countries announced readiness in the joint
communique to raise their trade volume five times from 20 million
U.S. dollars at present to 100 million dollars by the end of the
coming Iranian year (to start on March 21).
</P>
<P>
Before leaving here for Syria, Lukashenko said that the
agreements signed during his visit to Tehran were all in
conformity with the international criteria and target no other
country, the Iranian official news agency IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
He said that his negotiations with the Iranian officials
focused on promoting trade and economic cooperation between the
two countries, adding that Belarus would support Iranian
interests in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) and the
eastern European states while Iran in turn would support
Belarussian interests in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"I declare here that Minsk and Tehran believe in multipolar
world and that international system would be strong when it
remain multipolar," Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian President Mohammad Khatami said that Iran
and Belarus reached agreements on oil and gas and experts of
the two countries would start technical studies.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries have the same views concerning some
international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also stressed that the accords and close relations
between Iran and Belarus would harm no other country.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko arrived here Friday night for an official visit,
during which he held talks with Khatami and Vice President Hassan
Habibi and met with Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei. 
</P>
