<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urges U.S. to Pay U.N. Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Monday once again called on the United States to clear
its 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in back dues to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Annan, scheduled to pay a one-day visit to Washington on
Wednesday, made the appeal in an article carried in today's New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
He said when he meets with U.S. President Bill Clinton and his
administration officials during his visit, he is to discuss both
the Iraq and debt issues.
</P>
<P>
The doors of the bankrupt U.N. "are kept open only because
other countries in essence provide interest-free loans to cover
largely American-created shortfalls," he said.
</P>
<P>
A cash-starved U.N. can only benefit aggressors, violators of
human rights, drug dealers and international criminals and arms
merchants, while impeding humanitarian work, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said he has made a number of reforms, including
a U.N. budget cut and management tightening measures since he
came to office 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
A renewed partnership between the United Nations and the United
States is as much in the interest of the United States as the
United Nations, the Secretary-General said.
</P>
<P>
"But It has to be paid for," he said.  
</P>
