<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Reports on Final Procedures for Inspecting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday reported to the United Nations Security Council on
the finalization of procedures for inspecting Presidential sites
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Annan said the Special Group should comprise
senior diplomats, in the capacity of observers, appointed by the
Secretary-General of the United Nations and expers drawn from the
United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) and the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) in the number deemed appropriate by
the Executive Chairman of UNSCOM and the Director General of IAEA.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Special Group shall operate under
the established procedures of UNSCOM and the IAEA together with
specific detailed procedures given the special nature of the
Presidential sites, in line with the relevant resolutions of the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The report says the functions of the senior diplomats should
be: to observe that the provisions of the Memorandum of
Understanding and the present specific detailed procedures are
being implemented in good faith, to report on any matter they deem
appropriate to the functions of the diplomatic observers.
</P>
<P>
The functions of the experts from UNSCOM and IAEA are: to
determine the need for the performance of mandated tasks within
a Presidential site, to determine the date and time for entry
into the Presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
On the report of inspection of the Presidential sites, Annan
said it should be prepared by the Commissioner of the Special
Group appointed by the Secretary-General and submitted by the
Executive Chairman of UNSCOM to the Security Council through the
Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
Annan said these specific detailed procedures may be revised
from time to time in the light of experience in their implementation.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief and the Government of Iraq reached the Memorandum
of Understanding on February 23 which avoided a possible American
military strike against Iraq and ended the standoff between the
United Nations and Iraq over the weapons inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Memorandum, a U.N. Special Group will
be established to address Iraq's legitimate concerns relating to
national security, sovereignty and dignity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0063 </DOCNO>
