<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Leoneans Preparing for Kabbah's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The people in Freetown, capital of
Sierra Leone, are in a festival mood Monday, busy cleaning up to
welcome the return of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah from exile in
neighboring Guinea on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian community in Freetown is particularly happy as
some of them, who are in the city doing business, were seen
singing and dancing along the streets to the center of Freetown,
the British Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Many people fled Freetown after the military junta seized
power through a coup last May 25, ousting the democratically
elected government led by President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Life in Freetown has become very hard since Sierra Leone's
west African neighbors and the United Nations imposed economic
sanctions and arms embargo on the country in a bid to force the
junta to quit office.
</P>
<P>
When dialogue and sanctions failed, the west African
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG launched a military offensive
and dislodged the junta in Freetown in the middle of last month.
</P>
<P>
Things have since turned for the better day by day as the
much-awaited international relief goods began to arrive,
activities returned to government offices, shops, banks which all
closed during the rule of the junta.
</P>
<P>
Fuel, which was under strictly banned from entering Sierra
Leone in the past nine months, began to come back in Freetown
again over the weekend and the main roads from the capital to the
north of the country have been reopened to safe civilian traffic.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here Monday quoted oil industry officials as
saying that the current price of diesel was approaching its
pre-coup level in the capital and a ship containing gasoline had
already arrived.
</P>
<P>
Bus fares also dropped by half, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Although there are still not much food and drink in Freetown,
local people are said to be in high spirit because the junta has
gone and democracy has come back.
</P>
<P>
While continuing tracing the remnants of the junta forces and
allied rebels, ECOMOG is also beefing up security in Freetown for
Kabbah's return, expectedly in the company of General Sani
Abacha, chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) and Nigerian head of state.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that three other west African leaders would be
present at Kabbah's reinstatement ceremony in Freetown Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They are Ghanaian President Lansana Conte, Gambian President
Yayah Jammeh and Liberian President Charles Taylor, who the BBC
said, might not been welcomed by Sierra Leoneans because of his
support to the junta.
</P>
<P>
The presence of ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Couyate and
a U.N. delegation are also expected.
</P>
<P>
Last week, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he would
like to go to Freetown to attend the ceremony to celebrate
Kabbah's return personally or send a strong delegation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
