<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-09 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khufu Pyramid to Be Closed for Repair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Great Pyramid of Khufu (Cheops)
will be closed to tourists for eight months since April 1 to make
way for interior and exterior repairs, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pyramid of Khufu, the largest of the famous three Great
Pyramids in Giza, Cairo, dating back to the 4th Dynasty (2251-2528
BC), is Egypt's major tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
Zahi Hawas, director of antiquities for all of Giza, said
damage has been done to the interior of the Khufu Pyramid due to
poor ventilation. Humidity has reached a high level with mounting
numbers of visitors, causing salt crystals to build up on walls of
the inner chambers.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the eight months for repair, the exterior masonry
of the pyramid will be restored, the wooden staircase leading to
the chambers will be renovated, while new lighting, electricity
and ventilation systems will be installed, according to Hawas.
</P>
<P>
Gaballah Ali Gaballah, head of Egypt's antiquities authority,
Monday explained the move as part of an integrated project to
rehabilitate the surrounding Giza Plateau, which hosts the three
Great Pyramids and Sphinx.
</P>
<P>
The closure falls less than a month after the smallest of the
kings' pyramids in Giza, Menkaure, was reopened on March 3 after
18 months of restoration.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is building a camel and horse park to
keep camel owners from hawking tourists.
</P>
<P>
The Giza governorate has also built a huge fence to seal off
the antiquities areas from intruders from nearby villages.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the revamping of the pyramids area, however,
is yet to come. To mark the completion of 10 years of restoration
work on the Sphinx, celebrations are scheduled to take place at
the end of March.
</P>
<P>
There are estimated 6,000 tombs in the pyramids area alone,
only 46 of which are open to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Foreign Minister Begins Week-Long Talks in U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister
Saeed al-Sahaf Monday began a week of talks here with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and other U.N. leaders on the new
U.N. "oil-for-food" program.
</P>
<P>
Sahaf, who is leading a delegation of deputy ministers from
Iraq' oil, trade and health ministries, first met with Annan at
the Headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
He then had a meeting with new U.N. Deputy Secretary-General
Louise Frechette of Canada, who will now be in charge of Iraq's
"oil-for-food" program.
</P>
<P>
On February 20, the U.N. Security Council approved a proposal
by Britain and other countries to expand the oil selling level of
Iraq to 5.2 billion U.S. dollars for six months to improve the
growing humanitarian crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is currently allowed to sell only 2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil over six months to buy food, medicine and other goods
for its impoverished people.
</P>
<P>
The new program cannot begin until a detailed plan is worked
out for distributing goods.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of Sahaf's talks with Annan and other U.N.
leaders was to negotiate a better deal for the distribution plan,
Iraqi and U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi delegation is also expected to hold talks with U.N.
leaders on the implementation of a recent agreement between Annan
and the Iraqi leadership on arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, eight Iraqi presidential palaces will be
open to U.N. arms inspectors seeking to determine whether Iraq has
eliminate its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Annan Monday set rules for the procedure of arms inspections
in the Iraqi presidential palaces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
