<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:  Call for National Strike Defied Largely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Nengbiao)
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A planned one-day nation-wide
strike by Zambia's public service workers failed to take place
Monday as most of them reported for work across the country.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city of Lusaka, some government ministries have
registered a 100 percent turn-out.
</P>
<P>
According to a snap survey conducted by the Zambian News
Agency (Zana) late in the afternoon, workers were busy in their
offices while police kept vigil at the premises of the
ministries.
</P>
<P>
At the Finance Ministry, many workers said they hadd been
working normally since morning and all their colleagues had
reported for work.
</P>
<P>
At the Roads Department of the Ministry of Works and Supply,
all the workers had come for work, a senior engineering assistant
at the department Jonathan Chizalira said.
</P>
<P>
Policemen, some in full riot grear, kept guard also at the
downtown and the Zambia University Hospital, the largest hospital
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants in Luapula province in the north of the country
shunned the call by the Zambian Congress of Trade Union (ZCTU) to
force the government to rescind the planned wage freeze.
</P>
<P>
All public service workers in Mansa, the capital of the
province, reported for work Monday, although some workers might
have refrained from participating in the strike for fear of
losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Others said that local union leaders did nothing to publicize
the necessity of the strike.
</P>
<P>
They did not convene any meetings after the call for the
industrial action was made, they said.
</P>
<P>
Luapula Province Permanent Secretary Maybin Mubanga last
Friday managed to convince the workers not to participate in the
"illegal" nation-wide work stoppage because the matter was still
under negotiations between the government and labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
In Chipata, the capital city of Eastern Province, the strike
did not achieved its desired impact.
</P>
<P>
The only disruption in the provision of services to the public
was reported at local Chipata General Hospital where some labor
leaders werer understood to have harassed some medical staff,
urging them to stay away from their work.
</P>
<P>
The pharmacy reportedly closed and some patients at the
Out-Patient Department and the Chest Clinic with minor ailments
were turned away.
</P>
<P>
In Ndola, northern city of the country, almost all civil
servants in various government departments reported for work.
</P>
<P>
Some workers said they reported for work because of a
government circular last Friday issued a warning of stern action
to any worker who stays away from work Monday.
</P>
<P>
The workers however warned the government to quickly resolve
the issue of the wage freeze because they will not allow
themselves to be suppressed or intimidated forever.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a heavy presence of police officers clad in riot
gear were reportedly deployed in various parts of the town
center.
</P>
<P>
In other cities like Solwezi, Mufulira, Kitwe, Mongu and
Kabwe, the call was also largely defied.
</P>
<P>
But ZCTU President Fackson Shamenda said in Kitwe that he was
satisfied with the response of the workers in terms of the
government intimidation.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Labor Minister Newstead Zimba warned the
public service workers of instant dismissal if they take part in
the strike.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that unions organizing the strike risk being
de-registered because the planned work stoppage is illegal and
infringes on industrial law.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU General Secretary Alec Chirwa said early last week: "It
is unthinkable to impose a wage freeze on workers in a
liberalized economy" and "worse still the government is imposing
a wage freeze on workers who are earning far below a living wage,
this is the most inhuman treatment government can inflict on
workers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
