<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major S. African Banks Lower Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 9 (Xinhua) -- As expected, South Africa's major
banks Monday announced rate cuts by one percentage point as the newly
introduced repo rate takes effect.
</P>
<P>
South African leading banks, ABSA, First National Bank (FNB) and
Standard Bank, all lowered their prime lending rates and mortgage
rates.
</P>
<P>
ABSA group announced that it had dropped its prime lending rate
from 19.25 to 18.25 with effect from Thursday for both new and
existing accounts.
</P>
<P>
The standard mortgage or home loan interest rate would also be
lowered from 19 percent to 18 percent with effect from Thursday for
new loans and from April 1 for existing loans.
</P>
<P>
FNB announced a one percentage point cut in its home loan and prime
lending rates. Its home loan base mortgage rate would decrease to 18
percent with effect from next Monday for existing customers, while new
home loan customers would qualify for the new rate from Tuesday. Its
prime lending rate was lowered to 18.25 percent, effective Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank also lowered its prime lending rate to 18.25 percent
and home loan mortgage rate to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
South African Reserve Bank Saturday announced the introduction of
the new repo system, setting the repo rate at 15 percent between
Monday and Friday, one percentage point lower than the old bank rate.
</P>
<P>
The repo rate would be allowed to fluctuate from next Monday on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
