<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-09 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Parliament Debates New Draft Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese national assembly
(parliament) held an extraordinary session Monday to start debating
the new draft constitution.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, which was recalled from a recess that would have
normally ended early next month, is scheduled to debate the draft
until the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The draft will then be put to a nation-wide plebiscite at an
appropriate date so that it will be enforced by June 30 in
commemoration of the 9th anniversary of the revolution which
brought Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir to power.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir formed a committee last October to work out the draft
constitution which was completed in January.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the session, al-Bashir said that foremost among the
issues incorporated in the constitution is the cause of freedom.
</P>
<P>
He said that there have been five parliaments since
independence in 1956, but they have failed to draw up a
constitution acceptable to the majority of the Sudanese people.
</P>
<P>
The new draft constitution, he said, is rather comprehensive
and embraces the decrees promulgated by the salvation revolution.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government issued on June 30, 1989 a
constitutional decree to legitimize the performance of the
government in the absence of a constitution.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the first constitution in Sudan was
adopted in 1956 upon the country's independence. It was first
suspended in 1958, but was re-enforced in 1965.
</P>
<P>
The last constitution was suspended with the outbreak of
al-Bashir's national salvation revolution on June 30, 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
