<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Health-Related Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday urged Congress to pass health-related legislation this
year.
</P>
<P>
"I want it to go down in history as a Congress that saved
lives, by passing the patient bill of rights, by passing tough and
sweeping tobacco legislation," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an American Medical Association national conference,
Clinton renewed his call for Congress to pass legislation
establishing a "bill of rights" for the nearly 90 million people
enrolled in federal health care programs.
</P>
<P>
"There is utterly no reason not to do this this year," Clinton
said, noting that Congress has as few as 70 working days left
before adjourning for the fall election season.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration this week is expected to step up a
campaign for anti-tobacco legislation now stalled in Congress.
</P>
<P>
While noting that the tobacco issue is complicated by various
conflicting interests, Clinton said, "The big picture is clear:
every single day -- even though it is illegal in every state in
America -- 3,000 kids start to smoke. One thousand of them will
die early because of it. This amounts to a national epidemic and a
national tragedy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
