<HEADLINE> At Least Eight Dead in Southeast U.S. in Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- At least eight people were
killed and about 2,000 were evacuated in southern Alabama as the
region was flooded after a weekend of drenching rain sent a
swollen creek gushing through a break in a levee.
</P>
<P>
Emergency officials closed roads and warned the flooding might
continue for the next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino-powered storm also flooded creeks and streams in
much of Georgia and caused tornadoes in Florida Monday morning.
The storm has brought damage to retirement communities, mobile
home parks and campgrounds across Florida, leaving 150,000 people
without power.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen people were injured in Florida and one person was
killed in North Carolina Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The severe weather was part of a huge weather system that also
dropped up to 18 inches of snow across the Midwest, with drifts
standing more than three meters high Monday in Des Moines, Iowa.
More than 300 kilometers of Interstate 80 remained closed Monday
in Nebraska. 
</P>
</TEXT>
