<HEADLINE> Greece Urges Parties Concerned to Settle Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday called on the parties
concerned to resolve the Kosovo problem by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The Greek appeal came after Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
held talks with visiting Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani on
issues of the growing tension in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo
and the rights of the 300,000 ethnic Greeks living in southern
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Greece was unreservedly opposed to both terrorism and any
change in existing borders in the Balkan region, he said, adding
that Athens urged the parties involved to have "a sincere and
substantial dialogue" without preliminary conditions.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that this would lead to a resolution of the
problems of the region through the recognition of broad autonomy
in Kosovo without a change of borders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mejdani, who began Monday his first official visit
to Greece, said that the tension in Kosovo posed a threat to peace
and stability in the region. He called on Greece, the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU) to
help bring an end to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
As for Albanian-Greek relations, he described their ties as
"excellent," saying that Albania needed Greece's support in its
economic reforms and Greece would continue to back the neighboring
country's efforts to join Euro-Atlantic structures.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his arrival here, Mejdani also discussed with his
Greek counterpart Costis Stephanopoulos the situation in Kosovo,
where ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the nearly
two-million population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
