<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran: Ready to Improve Ties With Gulf States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran Monday reiterated readiness to
improve relations with the Gulf states, but called on them to
persuade the United Arab Emirates (UAE) to solve the territorial
disputes with Iran through "bilateral negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Iran is interested in broadening and strengthening of
relations with the regional countries, Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said, but adding there exists a need
to find common grounds for bringing about cooperation and exchange
of mutual views.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi made the remark in a response to the final statement
of the 66th foreign ministers' meeting of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC), the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The GCC foreign ministers announced in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia,
on Sunday that the GCC states welcomed improving relations with
Iran since they have seen "positive policy trends" from the
government of Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and the recent
visit of former Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani to Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that a new amicable atmosphere has been created
for cooperation between the GCC states and Iran after the election
of Khatami as Iran's new president last May.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran gives importance to the bolstering of further
friendly relations and cooperation with the GCC members, adding
that the cooperation among regional countries is a vital factor
for regional security and in settling disputes.
</P>
<P>
He expressed dissatisfaction with the GCC statement announcing
support for the UAE's claim on its sovereignty over the islands of
Abu Musa, the Greater and the Lesser Tunbs at the mouth of the
strategic Hormoz Strait.
</P>
<P>
Both Tehran and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty over the
three islands, which are mainly under Iran's control since the
British colonists withdrew from the region in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Tehran favors a bilateral negotiation to solve the issue while
Abu Dhabi attempts to seek a solution through the International
Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
The GCC foreign ministers also expressed "deep regret" that
Iran has not responded to the call by the UAE and the GCC to solve
the Tehran-Abu Dhabi dispute peacefully.
</P>
<P>
In return, Mohammadi stated that the Islamic Republic of Iran
expects the GCC to persuade UAE to reopen the door for bilateral
negotiations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran is all set to reactivate the stalled bilateral
negotiations with the UAE, he said, adding that a bilateral
negotiation is the only possible way of settling down of the
issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite the territorial dispute, Iran and the GCC states
warmed up their relations after Khatami's government stated to
pursue friendly and peaceful relations with regional countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
