<HEADLINE> No-Confidence Motions Against Israeli Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Monday rejected two motions of no-confidence, which accused the
coalition government of hindering the development of the economy.
</P>
<P>
In a special session of the Knesset, 45 members voted
against the motions and 42 voted for them, and 3 abstained.
</P>
<P>
Before the voting, opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak,
who presented one of the motions, said that Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu should hold responsibility for the
slowdown in economy and the high rate of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are currently 190,000 unemployed workers in
Israel, but the government remained deaf to the calls and cries of
the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Netanyahu has not kept his promises to develop the
economy and should go home.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Netanyahu of trying to hold back the
facts that the economy was slowing down. He said that the
recession was the result of Netanyahu's hard-line policy in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's coalition government currently has a slim majority
of 61 in the 120-seat Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
