<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Seeks International Charter on Electronic Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A senior European Commission
official reiterated the appeal for an international charter on
global electronic services.
</P>
<P>
A European Union press release Tuesday quoted Commissioner
Martin Bangemann as saying that in a borderless environment,
global problems require global solutions.
</P>
<P>
"At the very least, they (global problems) need to be addressed
in a consistent manner at international level," said the
commissioner during his weekend trip to the United States. He
urged for an open and market-led approach.
</P>
<P>
He called for an industrial round-table meeting which would be
a first step in the consensus building process leading up to an
international charter.
</P>
<P>
Bangemann also urged the private sector to play a more active
role in international communications policies.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner complained that governments and international
organizations tended too often to adapt yesterday's rules to
today's world, and often too slowly.
</P>
<P>
Market operators should lead in identifying bottlenecks and
priorities in global communications and information technology
issues, and bring them to the attention of governments worldwide
so that problems can be tackled in a global perspective, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that an improved, more coordinated international
agenda by both industry and governments is absolutely essential to
reducing the number of regulations required, and avoiding
uncertain, incompatible and fragmented rules," said Bangemann.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
union, early last month adopted a proposal by Bangemann, together
with Commission Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan, on strengthening
international coordination on electronic services.
</P>
<P>
The EU telecommunications ministers have endorsed the
commission's decision and asked the commission to submit a
progress report in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Following are major business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and the United Arab Emirates signed an agreement
for technical cooperation in the field of labor. The two sides
will exchange information about the labor market and cooperate in
the fields of safety and vocational training in accordance with
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The annual Cairo International Fair, which is due to
last 10 days, will open Wednesday. So far 45 countries have agreed
to participate in the fair.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony will be attended by 20 Arab, African
and Asian ministers of economy and trade. About 2,000 Egyptian
companies and 1,000 foreign ones will show their products at the
fair.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Chairman of the General Authority for Investment and
Free Zones in Egypt Ibrahim Fawzi said that during the first two
months of 1998, 378 new projects have been established in
accordance with the new investment law, compared with 33 projects
during the same period in 1997. Most of these projects are in the
fields of industry, tourism, services and farming sectors.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Crown Prince of the Dubai emirate, Sheikh Mohammed Ben
Rashed al Maktoum, inaugurated the biggest plant for hardened
color glass in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The plant, with an annual production capacity of 1.5 million
square meters, cost 70 million dirham (about 19 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
