<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crimes Against Women, Children Increase in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Crimes against women and
children are increasing in Nepal in the common forms of rape,
child prostitution, child marriage, child servitude, kidnapping
and child labor, said a report released recently in the country.
</P>
<P>
Marriage age in Nepal is very low. By the time they reach 15,
34 percent of women are already married and 10 percent bear
children, said the report called "State of the Rights of the Child
in Nepal, 1998" released by the Child Workers in Nepal Concern
Center (CWIN), an non-governmental organization in the country.
</P>
<P>
In some communities in the southern Terai plain, the tradition
of child marriage has children as young as seven years old engaged
for marriage, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Child abuse and neglect is very much a part of social reality
in Nepal, the report said, adding that in 1997 the CWIN had
recorded 587 reported child abuse cases all over the country
including rape, trafficking, missing and abduction, murder, child
marriage and excessive torture of child workers.
</P>
<P>
Street children are among the major victims of child abuse and
neglect in Nepal, the number of the cases stands at 5,000, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The exploitation of children through prostitution, pornography
and sex tourism is a growing form of commercialized violence, with
girls as the main victims.
</P>
<P>
And the trend of sexual violence and rape is increasing in both
rural and urban areas in Nepal. In 1997 the CWIN had recorded a
total of 110 cases of rape and sexual violence involving women and
children ranging in age from 18 months and 45 years, the report
noted.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 200,000 Nepalese women and children
who have been trafficked to India are forced into prostitution in
different parts of the country, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Child labor is also an integral part of Nepal. At least one
million children are working as child laborers and 40,000 are
bonded laborers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that children are made the victims of growing family
violence and crimes, adding that in 1997 it had recorded
altogether 47 cases of child killings including 21 of infant
murder.
</P>
<P>
About 75,000 children die every year in Nepal, with 55 percent
caused by malnutrition and about 13 percent by Hepatitis B, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of education, the report said about 3.2 million
children have enrolled in schools, accounting for only 68 percent
of the total school-aged children.
</P>
<P>
Despite equal constitutional rights to all children, gender
discrimination is more than obvious in every walk of life in
Nepal, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said girls are discriminated against boys from the moment of
birth. According to statistics, girls work two time more than boys
whereas their participation in school is almost two times less
than that of boys.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Official on Government Role in Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Hong Kong
official said here Tuesday that the government would strive to
create an environment to ensure the sustainable growth of the
productivity of the local industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang Yam-kuen ruled out the
possibility that the Special Administrative Region (SAR)
government would take a "pro-active" approach to encourage
industry, which many people said has been in decline.
</P>
<P>
"Many functions that used to be performed in house have been
farmed out ... So, much of what used to be counted as
manufacturing is now called services," Tsang said in a speech
Tuesday at the annual dinner of the Hong Kong Federation of
Industries.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong manufacturers have moved their factories and
workshops to southern China and Southeast Asia to take advantage
of the cheap labor and low rents there. The financial secretary
said: "It's just that the nature of industry and its environment
impact has changed."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that what was really important for Hong Kong is
productivity. According to the official, Hong Kong keeps an
average annual increase of 13.7 percent in productivity, which
sets the economy apart from most regional competitors.
</P>
<P>
"My colleagues and I are determined to act vigorously and act
consistently to ensure that you have an environment in which you
can maintain those vital gains in productivity," he told the
participants.
</P>
<P>
The government would work hard to improve the quality of
education, upgrade infrastructure, and take other actions to help
increase the productive capacity of Hong Kong economy, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
