<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Noted Religious Figures Calling for Enacting Law on Religion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A noted Chinese Buddhist proposed
that a law on religion be enacted to deal with new developments in
the religious field.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Puchu, head of the Buddist Association of China, said
the rule of law is what China is pursuing.
</P>
<P>
Without a national religious law, a religious legal system
cannot take shape in China no matter how many local laws and
administrative regulations are adopted governing religious
activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao, also a vice-chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, who is present
at the annual CPPCC session, said religious work in China is to
carry out the policy of freedom of religious belief. "The
principle will remain unchanged," said Zhao.
</P>
<P>
China has five religions, namely Buddhism, Taoism, Catholicism,
Islam and Christianity with more than 100 million believers
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials reiterated not long ago that China will
continue to implement a policy of religious freedom while
administering religious affairs according to law.
</P>
<P>
Fu Tieshan, head of the Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association
and bishop of the Beijing Diocese, said that to manage religious
affairs according to law will not contradict religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
With a law in place, religious properties and religious places
will be better protected, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bishop noted that religious bodies are social organizations
which own different facilities and organize various activities.
They should be put in the framework of the country's legal system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
