<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ninth NPC First Session Passes Election, Appointment Methods (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The third plenary meeting of the
First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) this
afternoon adopted the Election and Appointment Methods for this
session.
</P>
<P>
The 19-article election and appointment methods have been
worked out in accordance with specifications in the Constitution
of the People's Republic of China (PRC) and other relevant laws.
</P>
<P>
According to the methods, the nominees for chairman,
vice-chairmen, secretary-general and members of the NPC Standing
Committee, the nominees for president and vice-president of the
PRC, the nominee for chairman of the Central Military Commission
and the nominees for president of the Supreme People's Court and
procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate are
nominated by the presidium of the First Session.
</P>
<P>
Following deliberations and consultations by NPC delegations,
the presidium determines formal nominees in accordance with the
opinions of most deputies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the methods noted, the nominees for chairman,
vice-chairmen, secretary-general and members of the NPC Standing
Committee must be nominated from among NPC deputies.
</P>
<P>
The candidate for the premier of the State Council is nominated
by the president of the PRC, the nominees for vice-premiers of the
State Council, state councillors, ministers, chairmen of various
commissions, governor of the People's Bank of China,
auditor-general and the secretary-general are nominated by the
premier of the State Council, the methods added.
</P>
<P>
The nominees for vice-chairmen and members of the Central
Military Commission of the PRC are nominated by the chairman of the
Central Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth NPC Standing Committee has a members of 155 persons.
The elections for chairman, vice-chairmen and secretary-general of
the Standing Committee are conducted by way of
one-candidate-for-one-post, whereas Standing Committee members are
elected through multi-candidate election, with a five-percent
proportion of candidates not to be elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
