<HEADLINE> 88th Yonex All-England Open Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, ENGLAND, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A total of 320
competitors representing 58 countries and areas have gathered here
for the start of the Yonex All-England Open Championships Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
China, which took four of the five titles last year, sent 21
competitors to the Championships hoping to keep its supremacy in
the badminton world.
</P>
<P>
However, the miss of name Dong Jiony, the All-England men's
champion, in name list caused surprise among observers here.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to find the reason why", a spokesman for the
organizers said. "It's disappointing to lose the defending
champion, of course, but it will not detract from the event."
</P>
<P>
Owing to financial hardship caused by the economic crisis in
the Far East, some Asian countries have sent smaller squads to
this year's championships, but all the big names in the area are
present.
</P>
<P>
As far as British players are concerned, it is the first time
in the tournament's 99-year history that no home players have been
seeded.
</P>
<P>
But England National Coach Asger Madsen said on Monday "Our
players have prepared well for the Championships. They have been
training hard and I expect this effort to be reflected in their
performance."
</P>
<P>
However, observers here believe that it will take time before
England can approach the standard of the Asian players.  
</P>
</TEXT>
