<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Tackles from Behind to Be Punished, FIFA Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- FIFA told coaches and referees
Tuesday that all tackles from behind should be punished with a red
card at the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
"All tackling from behind is considered to endanger the
physical integrity of the opponent, so no tackling from behind
will be tolerated by FIFA," a report quoted the world body's
general secretary Sepp Blatter as saying.
</P>
<P>
The International Football Association Board, the game's
law-making body, passed an amendment to Law 12 on fouls and
misconduct at a meeting last month.
</P>
<P>
The amendment designates the tackle from behind as serious foul
play and therefore a sending-off offence, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, referees at the workshop wondered whether the tackle
had physically to endanger a player for the tackler to be sent off.
</P>
<P>
Coaches and referees at the workshop asked for clarification of
the new ruling, and Blatter told them that all tackles from behind
should receive red cards.
</P>
<P>
"It's impossible for the referee to see if a tackle is
dangerous or not because all tackles (from behind) put in danger
the physical integrity of the opponent," Blatter was quoted as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
