<HEADLINE> International Seminar on Ganges Barrage Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The three-day international seminar
on the feasibility of the proposed Ganges Barrage project in
Bangladesh ended here Tuesday after adopting a three-point plan of
action.
</P>
<P>
Under the action plan, the studies would assess the technical
and economic viability of the project, such as its impact on the
environment and the social and economic development in the
surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
Participants pledged to support the feasibility study of the
project, to determine the optimal use of the Ganges water
resources made available following the signing of a 30-year Ganges
water sharing treaty between Bangladesh and India in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The feasibility study of the project was expected to start
within four or five months and the construction of the project
would take about four years after necessary studies were
completed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The water sharing treaty had opened the opportunity of
undertaking projects for the development of the Ganges water
resources, Prime Minster Sheikh Hasina said at the inaugural
session of the seminar jointly organized by the Bangladeshi Water
Resources Ministry, Japan, the World Bank, and the Asian
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to act now on the best possible option...for
improving the life and livelihood for our people on the water of
the Ganges," she said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, on "water resources management and development in
Bangladesh with particular reference to the Ganges River," was
attended by some 150 delegates, including 59 from foreign
countries and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The much-talked-about barrage near Bhanga, Faridpur, some 112
kilometers northwest of here, has been planned for protecting the
southwest region of the country which reports said has been
seriously affected by the Farakka Barrage of India.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the barrage was needed to utilize the Ganges
water properly, after the signing of the Ganges water sharing
treaty, to protect the world's largest mangrove forest of
Sundarban, maintain environmental balance and ensure
socio-economic development in the southwestern region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
