<HEADLINE> Guangdong Improves Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province,
the pacesetter of China's economic reform, has made much progress
in legislation, said Zhu Senlin, chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Guangdong Provincial People's Congress (GPPC),
here today.
</P>
<P>
Legislation by local governments is a supplement to legislation
by the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has been playing its role as an "experimental ground"
in the field of legislation, he said at a panel discussion
attended by deputies to the Ninth National People's Congress, in
session here since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the Standing Committee of the Guangdong
Provincial People's Congress has drawn up 151 local laws and
regulations, more than any previous standing committees, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five percent of the laws and regulations, numbering 99,
cover the fields of market economics, economic management,
ecological protection and promotion of scientific and
technological progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
The province has also supervised the enforcement of these laws
and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said his province will enhance education on legal knowledge
among its people, improve the law enforcement system, and raise
the quality of its legislators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
