<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK NPC Deputies Encouraged by Jiang's Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Deputies from the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) to the Ninth National People's
Congress, China's top legislature, in session here since last
Thursday, said today that they have been greatly encouraged by a
speech made by President Jiang Zemin in a panel discussion with
them on Monday.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that Jiang's speech has reflected the firm
resolution of the central government to implement the principle of
"one country, two systems" and will further improve people's
confidence in Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Joseph Lee Chung-tak, who is chairman of the Hong Kong
United Youth Association, noted that Jiang didn't raise any demand
on Hong Kong's future development or the operation of the SAR
government, as he usually did in panel discussions with NPC
delegations from other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
"This difference shows that the central government has kept its
promise of not interfering with Hong Kong's internal affairs and
has highly trusted the SAR government," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Raymond Wu Wai-yung, a member of the Hong
Kong SAR Basic Law Committee under the NPC Standing Committee,
Jiang's speech is both comprehensive and realistic, and his
analysis of Hong Kong's current situation and future prospects is
very inspiring and encouraging.
</P>
<P>
"President Jiang explicitly analyzed the basic conditions for
Hong Kong to preserve its long-term prosperity and stability. This
will greatly help us to see our own advantages, maintain full
confidence and make concerted efforts to overcome difficulties,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Fei Fih, UNICEF executive member in Hong Kong, said that
Hong Kong people have felt the central government's great concerns
and resolute backing for Hong Kong's prosperity and stability
throughout the transitional period before Hong Kong's return and
the eight months and more after the return.
</P>
<P>
"It's all because of this that Hong Kong people can maintain a
strong confidence in the face of negative economic impact," she
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
