<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Stays Atop with 12 Gold Medals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Norway showed its prowess in
cross-country ski race Tuesday with taking three golds, which
boosted the country to stay atop the gold medal standings with 12
at the Nagano Winter Paralympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Ragnhild Myklebust, 54, won her third gold medal and 15th in
her Paralympic career by snatching the crown in the women's
5-kilometer race for athletes with lower limb disabilities in 19
minutes, 19.9 seconds on a ski-equipped sledge.
</P>
<P>
Colette Bourgonje of Canada was second.
</P>
<P>
Tone Gravvold, accompanied by guide Frode Nilssen, won the
women's 5-kilometer cross country race for partially sighted
athletes.
</P>
<P>
Karl Einar Henriksen won the men's 10-kilometer sit-ski race
for athletes with disabilities in both lower limbs.
</P>
<P>
Finland's Karl Joki-Erkkila won the men's 10-kilometer sit-ski
race for athletes with less severe lower limb disabilities.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 10-kilometer race for partially sighted athletes,
Irek Mannanov of Russia took the title.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Norway and Canada entered the Friday's
semifinals after beating the United States 2-0 and Japan 3-0
respectively in Pool B ice sledge hockey round-robin preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, Estonia and Britain in Pool A were idle Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Germany stands second in gold medal standings with 10 after
Norway's 12, while Japan and Russia have eight each.
</P>
<P>
The Paralympics, which opened last Thursday with 590 disabled
athletes from a record 32 delegations, will end on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
