<HEADLINE> Asian Financial Turmoil Affects Shanghai Export Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The financial turmoil in Asia
has had a dampening effect on the '98 East China Export Commodity
Fair, which runs from March 5 to March 14 in Shanghai, fair
officials say.
</P>
<P>
In the first five days, 4,500 businessmen have visited the fair
and daily trading stood at 102 million US dollars, down 16 percent
and 17.4 percent, respectively, from last year's fair.
</P>
<P>
The annual event, which started in 1991, is sponsored by
Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Shandong, Fujian, Anhui, and Jiangxi provinces,
Shanghai, and the cities of Nanjing and Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
Most of the overseas participants are from Asia, but this year
the number from Indonesia and the Republic of Korea is down
drastically, while the number of Europeans and Americans was down
by less than 10 percent, and the number of businessmen from West
Asia, Africa, South America and Oceania has increased 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
European countries and the United States now rank first and
second, respectively, in trading for the first time, and the three
former leaders, Hong Kong, Macao, and Japan have taken the back
seat.
</P>
<P>
Hi-tech products and large enterprises from Anhui, Zhejiang and
Shanghai have been active, but textiles and light industrial goods
are in the lead, officials say, and predict even more active
trading in the coming days. However, they believe that this year's
trading will lag behind last year's 2.23 billion US dollars
worth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
