<HEADLINE> Shanghai Is Focusing On Improved Bank Services For 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 10 (Xinhua) -- China's financial center,
Shanghai, will improve the quality of local bank services and open
its banking sector wider to the outside world this year.
</P>
<P>
Mao Yingliang, the president of the Shanghai Branch of the
People's Bank of China, China's central bank, told a meeting on
foreign investment and foreign financial institutions that the
major tasks this year are helping foreign financial institutions
develop their business locally, ensuring safe and efficient
operations in the city's financial sector, and helping score
sustained, rapid, and healthy economic development.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will reinforce its position as the financial center of
the country, Mao said, and more foreign banks are expected to set
up offices in Shanghai and the scope of their services will expand
to offshore banking.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government will encourage Chinese and foreign
financial institutions to set up branches in the Pudong New Area
to improve the Lujiazui Financial Center, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks are being invited to undertake infrastructure
projects, he said, and are even being encouraged to do business
outside the city.
</P>
<P>
There will be tighter supervision over foreign financial
institutions, especially those that are headquartered in countries
that have suffered from the current financial crisis in Asia, Mao
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
