<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe, South Korea to Form Anti-Dumping Database </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission -- the
European Union's executive body -- announced on Tuesday that it
has approved agreements between Europe and South Korea to create a
database for anti-dumping procedures.
</P>
<P>
Karel van Miert, the European commissioner responsible for
competition policy, approved the agreements entered into by the
European Electronic Component Manufacturers Association, the Korea
Semiconductor Industry Association and their respective member
companies.
</P>
<P>
The agreements provide for the creation of a data collection
and maintenance system for dynamic random access memories (DRAMs)
and flash erasable, programmable, read-only memories (Flash
EPROMs).
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the database is to provide expeditious
resolutions for anti-dumping procedures, says an EU spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
Participating manufacturers will collate their company-specific
data on cost of production and sale prices for DRAMs and Flash
EPROMs and supply the information to an independent agency.
</P>
<P>
The European Union and the independent agency will have access
to the information in the event of anti-dumping complaints or
trade disputes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
