<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and Figures about Indonesia: Indonesia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The General Session of the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), Indonesia's highest
legislative body, Tuesday entered its climax by re-electing
incumbent President Soeharto to his seventh term of office.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the nation's highest legal body was a smooth
affair, reflecting Indonesia's preference for politics by
consensus rather than by confrontation.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, the president and vice-president are elected once
every five years by an oral vote of the 1,000-strong MPR, over
half of whose members are directly appointed by the president.
</P>
<P>
The MPR includes the 425 members of parliament (MPs) directly
elected in Parliamentary elections and another 75
president-appointed MPs from the Armed Forces, plus a further 500
presidential appointees.
</P>
<P>
Recognized political parties, of which there are only three in
Indonesia, are invited to put forward presidential candidates to
the MPR's five-yearly General Assembly Session, which is usually
held from March 1 to 11.
</P>
<P>
However, no rival candidates have been presented since Soeharto
came to power 32 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, 76, was renominated early last month by the ruling
party Golkar and then the powerful Armed forces and regional
representatives expressed their support to the renomination. The
two minority party -- the United Development Party (PPP) and the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) also received Soeharto as the
only candidate of president at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
"Since there was only one presidential candidate, according to
the law Soeharto is automatically formalized as president," the
chairman of the Assembly Harmoko announced Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The MPR members stood up and applauded. There was no
dissenters.
</P>
<P>
The MPR will also elect a vice president and endorse State
Policy Guidelines for the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
