<HEADLINE> Ritter's Inspection Team Leaves for Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. arms inspection team
headed by the American Scott Ritter left here for Bahrain Tuesday,
after finished its work "perfectly and without any problems."
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Hussam Mohammed Ameen, director of Iraqi
National Monitoring Department, the Iraqi counterpart of the
U.N. Special Commission on scrapping Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted Ameen as saying that Ritter's team
ended its work three days before schedule and left here for
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
"Scott Ritter informed the Iraqi side that he had accomplished
his mission perfectly and without any problems, thanking the Iraqi
side for cooperating with his team," Ameen said.
</P>
<P>
Ritter's 50-member team, which included 12 Americans, six
Britons and 10 Australians, arrived here last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In mid-January, a 16-member inspection team headed by Ritter
was barred from carrying out any activities by the Iraqi
government on grounds that its composition was imbalanced. That
team included nine Americans and five Britons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other arms inspection teams continued their routine
activities Tuesday with full cooperation from the Iraqi side, said
Ameen.
</P>
<P>
Ameen said 10 inspection groups visited 17 sites which are
under monitoring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
