<HEADLINE> Private Entrepreneurs Get Rights To Be Model Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 10 (Xinhua) -- For the first time in China,
private businesses have been given permission to be recognized as
"model workers", after the federation of trade unions of Shandong
Province pushed for this recently, saying that private
entrepreneurs should be given the right.
</P>
<P>
In the past, only staff and workers of state-owned and
collectively-owned enterprises and farmers could compete for the
honor, but the policies worked out at the 15th National Party
Congress made the change possible, according to Wang Xinghai,
director of the federation's production and protection department.
</P>
<P>
The Party Congress, which was held last September, removed some
of the worries about ownership, and new policies in many places
have helped develop the private sector.
</P>
<P>
In Shandong alone, by the end of 1997, there were 2.54 million
family businesses, employing 5.46 million people, and 77,000
private enterprises with more than a million employees.
</P>
<P>
People working in the private sector now account for 11.5
percent of the province's total number of employees, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
Wang says the private economy has become a major part of the
social productive forces, the rural economy, and a major source
of employment.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Guangdong Province approved the
nomination of the country's first private-businessman model
worker, but Shandong has become the first to make it official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
