<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Test Tube Baby Celebrates 10th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- China's first test-tube baby,
Zheng Mengzhu, celebrated her 10th birthday in Beijing today at
the invitation of Beijing Medical University's No. 3 Hospital,
where she was born.
</P>
<P>
She said that she was happy that so many people came to
celebrate. More than 20 children who were test-tube babies were
present.
</P>
<P>
Zheng was born March 10, 1988. She weighed 3.9 kg. There were
many reports about her in China, calling it an important event in
reproduction and a milestone in dealing with sterility through
modern methods.
</P>
<P>
"She was a very lovely baby," said Dr. Zhang Lizhu, who created
the first test-tube baby in China.
</P>
<P>
Zheng's mother, Zheng Guizhen is a primary school teacher in
north China's Gansu Province. She was 39 years old then and did
not become pregnant 20 years after her marriage.
</P>
<P>
She says her daughter has been very healthy and began school at
the age of five and is a good student.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Mengzhu's father said that Mengzhu is 1.5 meters tall and
weighs 40 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
No.3 Hospital has had more than 200 test tube babies, and a
success rate of 25 percent. A dozen hospitals in China have the
service and have had about 1,000 test tube babies.
</P>
<P>
The world's first test tube baby was born in Britain in 1978,
according to Dr. Zhang, who is now retired. 
</P>
</TEXT>
