<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sends 2006 World Cup Signals (Correction) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is already looking beyond
the hosting of the FIFA Youth Championship next year as it
prepares for the 2006 World Cup, a Nigerian official said in Abuja
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Youth and Sports Minister Air Commodore Emeka Omeruah
said after signing a contract for the rehabilitation of 10
stadiums in the country that the number of stadium has been
increased from eight to 10 to meet FIFA's requirement for hosting
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of work on the 10 stadiums, Nigeria will be
in comfortable position to bid for the hosting of the year 2006
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Omeruah's remark is the first official reaction to a recent
report that FIFA has asked Nigeria and South Africa to bid for the
year 2006 World Cup, saying that it is willing to give the hosting
right to an African country for the first time in history.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the successful hosting of the 1999
FIFA Youth Championship will be a major boost to Nigeria's bidding
for the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Another possible boost will come from Nigeria's national
football team, the Super Eagles, if the 1996 Atlanta Olympic
champion could meet the wide high expectation on it at the France
World Cup this June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
