<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar Agrees to Deployment of U.S. Surveillance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has agreed to the
deployment of P-3 surveillance aircraft by the United States on
its soil later this year, the official Qatari News Agency reported
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a telephone consultation last
week between Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa al-Thani and
U.S. President Bill Clinton, Qatari Foreign Ministry spokesman
Fawaz al Attiyah told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
But he did not elaborate on the number of the planes to be
deployed and how long they would be stationed in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The stationing of the aircraft will be "temporary" and "in the
context of a defense cooperation agreement" between Doha and
Washington, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and the U.S. signed a defense cooperation accord after
the 1991 Gulf War, which drove the Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
</TEXT>
