<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Enterprises Pursuing "Name-Brand Strategy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Companies in some Chinese
provinces have been encouraged by local governments to create
name-brand goods to improve their competitiveness, according to
a government official.
</P>
<P>
Qin Yongfa, a State Economic and Trade Commission official,
made the remark while addressing an international symposium on
name-brand strategies, in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The action comes as a result of the fact that the domestic
market is well on its way to becoming a buyers' market and a large
group of trans-enterprises have entered the Chinese market and
challenged Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy has become more closely tied to the global
economy in recent years, Qin said, with imports and exports
accounting for 40 percent of the country's economy, and with 200
of the world's top 500 companies doing business in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese enterprises have come to see that they can only count
on quality, new techniques, and good service if they are to
compete in the world market, Qin pointed out.
</P>
<P>
South China's Guangdong Province has already started a
name-brand project, and 180 of its name-brand products had 94.5
billion yuan in sales and about two billion US dollars in exports
in 1997..
</P>
<P>
The name-brand strategy is still at a preliminary stage in
China, he said, and Chinese name-brand goods still cannot hold
their own against international brands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
