<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Calls for Experiment on Euthanasia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese lawmaker suggested here
today that China should enact a law on euthanasia, or mercy
killing, and allow hospitals in some large cities to start the
practice of euthanasia on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
"China is expected to become an aged society by 2000. It's
already high time that we took the issue of euthanasia into
consideration," said Hu Yamei, a deputy to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, in session here
since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 75-year-old Hu, who is honorary president of Beijing
Children's Hospital, put forth the same suggestion at previous NPC
sessions as a lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
Beijing and Shanghai are the two cities where Hu suggested for
the earliest experiments of mercy killing.
</P>
<P>
"Euthanasia can only be applied to patients suffering from
incurable diseases under the precondition that it is the patients'
own wishes and has the consent of their family members," said Hu.
"It also must be approved by local civil affairs departments and
carried out in designated hospitals."
</P>
<P>
She noted that each year she receives letters from many people,
especially from retired revolutionary veterans, who expressed
great concern about progress regarding the issue of euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
"Mercy killing can relieve the patients of great pains, save
unnecessary medical expenses and reduce the psychological and
economic burdens of the patients' families," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
She called it a misconception that only longevity indicates
social progress, and said that a modern society should have modern
ethics on life.
</P>
<P>
She also blamed traditional Chinese culture and ideas and
feudal superstition for hindering the practice of mercy killing.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, China's news media have been involved in
several fruitless debates on the legality of euthanasia, which is
also in dispute in most parts of the world. Only a few nations
have reportedly greenlighted mercy killing on a trial basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
