<HEADLINE> New Police Warning System Operating In Southern Delta Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Police in south China's
Guangdong Province today began using a satellite-based warning
system to improve security in the Pearl River Delta.
</P>
<P>
The network is being used offshore near Zhuhai, Huizhou, Hong
Kong and Macao, according to provincial police officers involved
in offshore security. Police boats using the system have been
equipped with a ground positioning system (GPS).
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the local police have experimented with setting up
an offshore warning system in some coastal cities to crack down on
smuggling and pirate operations.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 million yuan has been spent on the project, and an
integrated police service system is expected to take shape in
Guangdong's coastal area by June.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the offshore warning system has been
used in 6,000 criminal cases, involving 11 groups of pirates and
200 instances of smuggling and trafficking in contraband. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
