<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Mahathir's Yangon Visit Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The two-day official visit of
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad to Myanmar, which ended
here Tuesday, has further strengthened the bilateral ties between
Myanmar and Malaysia, bringing the bilateral cooperation including
trade and economic cooperation to a new stage, some observers here
said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's first trip to the country after Myanmar's entry into
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) last July also
marked part of Malaysia's efforts to enhance bilateral ties with
neighboring countries and consolidate ASEAN unity.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar official media said Mahathir's visit is a milestone in
the annals of bilateral relations and the visit has also further
strengthened the existing ties and enhanced better understanding
on issues of national and regional interest.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar takes Mahathir as its strong ally when he put up a
stiff fight to get Myanmar into ASEAN amid obstructions by a
western group, the media said.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Mahathir were his wife Siti Hasmah, Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, Deputy Minister of International
Trade and Industry Kerk Choo Ting and Secretary-General of
Ministry of Foreign Affairs Datuk Abdul Kadir.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Mahathir held talks with Senior-General Than
Shwe, chairman of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council
and prime minister. The details of the talks were not officially
available, however, it is believed that the two sides have
reconfirmed their identity of views on subjects of mutual concern
and the need to work together for peace, prosperity and stability
of the region.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on avoidance of double taxation and prevention of
fiscal evasion with respect to taxes on income and a memorandum of
understanding on mutual exemption of visas for holders of
diplomatic and official passports were signed.
</P>
<P>
Concluding his two-day official visit to myanmar, Mahathir told
a press briefing that his talks with the Myanmar side focused on
the two countries' economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke to Myanmar to use each other's currency as other
ASEAN fellow members to promote intra-regional trade, adding that
his country would strive for a balance of bilateral trade since
the balance has long been in Malaysia's favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
