<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Mahathir's Yangon Visit Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since then, Malaysia has encouraged its private sector to
participate in trade and investment in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Some Malaysian firms began establishing wood-based industry and
manufacturing industry in Myanmar's Shwepyithar and Pyinmabin
industrial zones on contracts in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
Hoteliers stepped in taking up some hotel projects and at the
same time they extended hotel business training to Myanmar youths
in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Under the two countries' technical cooperation program, Myanmar
technicians were trained in Malaysia which contributed to the
development of human resources in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also provided nurses and doctors to meet Malaysia's
needs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the two countries were prepared to take part in
setting up a railway linking ten Southeast Asian countries and
China, which was discussed during visits of Malaysian Transport
Minister Ling Liong Sik to Myanmar in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Malaysia expanded its investment in Myanmar by being
engaged in the infrastructural development of the country's
largest foreign-invested industrial zone -- Thanlyin-Kyauktan --
in the capital with the Gentine Co. taking up the project of
building four container wharves out of 17 at the zone.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, two more Malaysian firms were also
respectively involved in the exploration and production of oil
and natural gas in the country's Tanintharyi coast and generation
and distribution of electricity in the southern part of the nation
on contracts.
</P>
<P>
More and more Malaysian entrepreneurs came on study tours
later, seeking for business venture opportunities with Myanmar
counterparts through business forums.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Malaysia brought in capital
of 587 million U.S. dollars in 25 permitted projects at the end of
1997, standing as the fourth largest foreign investor in Myanmar
after Britain, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the two countries' bilateral trade ties, it has been
 maintained for the last several decades with relatively small
volume. However, it grew from 64.8 million U.S. dollars in 1992-93
fiscal year to 192 million dollars in 1996-97 ended in March,
traditionally favoring Malaysia in the balance of trade, according
to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures indicate that the two countries' bilateral
trade amounted to 151 million dollars in the first ten months of
1997, up from 88.5 million dollars in the same period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Malaysia established diplomatic relations in early
1958. The exchange of visits of the two countries' state leaders
in two recent years significantly contributed to the further
development of their bilateral ties and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
