<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Trial Futures Market Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- China Zhengzhou Commodity
Exchange (CZCE), the country's first market for grain futures
trading on a trial basis, has become the world's 15th largest in
terms of transaction volume, said CZCE chairman Li Jingmou here
today.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is in Beijing attending the annual session of the
National People's Congress, said the Zhengzhou market's regulatory
functions on grain prices has been accepted by China's central
government and international futures trading circles as well.
</P>
<P>
Futures trading, considered a way to reform China's grain
circulation system, began first as an experiment in China. After
grain futures trading has proved successful and relevant laws are
enacted, it is expected to be introduced to other areas.
</P>
<P>
The grain circulation system is one of the five economic areas
where reform will be carried out this year, according to Chen
Jinhua, minister in charge of the State Planning Commission,
delivering a speech at the ongoing session of the NPC.
</P>
<P>
Conditions are ripe now for such a reform, said Li Jingmou, who
enumerated the following reasons to support his view:
</P>
<P>
-- Good agriculture harvests for three consecutive years,
providing ample grain reserves for reform;
</P>
<P>
-- The establishment of a grain reserve system with 7.5
billion kg in reserves able to stabilize grain prices;
</P>
<P>
-- The establishment of a grain marketing system.
</P>
<P>
"It's high time for China to push ahead with such a reform,"
said Li, who also acknowledged that such a reform must be
conducted in a prudent way since it concerns the interests of 800
million Chinese farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
