<HEADLINE> UNICEF Donating Funds To Chinese Earthquake Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHANGJIAKOU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) has pledged a 750,000-US-dollar donation for relief
work in earthquake-stricken parts of northern China around the
city of Zhangjiakou.
</P>
<P>
The funds come from the Hong Kong UNICEF Committee and the
Disaster Relief Fund Advisory Committee of Hong Kong and will be
used for tents, medical facilities, and teaching materials,
according to Keshab B. Mathema, UNICEF's China representative, who
is heading a mission to assess the needs of the disaster area.
</P>
<P>
He says he is satisfied with the local government's relief work
and was impressed by people's lives returning to normal and
children going back to school, after visiting two villages in
Zhangbei County on Monday.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF is one of a number of international organizations that
provided quick assistance when the magnitude 6.2 earthquake hit
the Zhangjiakou area on January 10, killing 50 people, injuring
more than 2,000, and leaving some 40,000 families
homeless. Economic losses have been estimated at about 2.4 billion
yuan (289 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that more than 1.9 billion yuan will be
needed for the rebuilding work.  
</P>
