<HEADLINE> French Coach Jacquet to Quit after World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The coach of France's national
soccer team, Aime Jacquet, will hand over his job after the World
Cup, a French soccer magazine said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jacquet took over the French team from Gerard Houillier in
February 1994, and said that four years coaching the team was
enough.
</P>
<P>
"When I accepted the job, I told the French Federation
president I would prepare and win the World Cup and afterwards I
would be finished with high level competition," he was quoted as
saying by soccer weekly France Football.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year-old said Alan Giresse, a midfield star of the 1982
and 1986 World Cup teams who is currently in charge of first
division Toulouse, would be his ideal successor.
</P>
<P>
The French team was in the top 10 of the FIFA rankings over the
past year under Jacquet's coaching. 
</P>
