<HEADLINE> Guangdong Province Helping Handicapped Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has helped disabled persons over the past year,
Vice-governor Ou Guangyuan told a meeting of the local association
of disabled persons today, by helping nearly 30,000 cataract
sufferers and performing 3,445 orthopedic operations.
</P>
<P>
Some 828 deaf pupils were placed in schools and training was
provided for 1,553 retarded pre-school age children.
</P>
<P>
The province provided funds for 3,211 extremely short-sighted
people to help improve their eyesight and provided 652,600 people
with much needed iodine pills.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Guangdong had established 13 rehabilitation
centers and 61 service bases for disabled persons, Ou said, and
the 51 special schools trained 33,000 young people with
disabilities. Another 9,753 disabled children who live in poverty
got help from various sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 28 students with disabilities have been enrolled
by local universities, sources say, and 3,000 people with
disabilities found jobs in 1997. 
</P>
