<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Slightly Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
retreated from its highs to close slightly firmer Tuesday, with
few leads from overseas markets dampening enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index rose 12.2 points to 2692.9, after
moving above 2700 points during the day.
</P>
<P>
"It was quiet on Wall Street. We just took our leads on the
banks. It was pretty lackluster overall," Brett O'Donovan from
Henderson Charlton Jones said.
</P>
<P>
One notable movement was that of resources giant BHP, which
escalated to 16.00 Australian dollars before a late fall dragged
it down to 15.594, amid market concern it would not reach its
targeted output at the Hartley platinum project in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index dropped one point to 1158.1 after BHP's
late drop.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to BHP's fall, resources major WMC rose six cents,
Rio Tinto rose 22.4 cents and Woodside added nine cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 1.7 points to 1102.2 as bullion price rose
0.10 US dollars per ounce to 294.50 at Sydney trading close.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index improved 27.3 points to 4616.7 as
Telstra interim receipts came back into favor after recent falls,
rising nine cents to 3.67 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks generally improved. National Australia Bank
gained 22 cents, ANZ added six, Westpac closed six cents better as
well and Commonwealth was three cents higher.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 262.2 million shares worth 721.48 million
Australian dollars (483.4 million US dollars) with rises
outnumbering falls by 559 to 496. 
</P>
