HONG KONG, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Gross sales of unit trusts in
January 1998 slumped to 203 million U.S. dollars, the lowest since
November 1995, the Hong Kong Investment Funds Association (HKIFA)
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Continuing uncertainties over the outcome of the Asian
financial crisis and further falls in regional currencies produced
extremely slack inflows in the first month of the year, HKIFA
Chairman Peter Lord said.
</P>
<P>
With redemption hitting 261 million U.S. dollars, the month
recorded net outflows of 59 million U.S. dollars. This was also
the fourth consecutive month that the industry registered net
outflows.
</P>
<P>
The industry recorded net outflows of 88 million U.S. dollars
in the fourth quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
"However," Lord pointed out, "it seems that, on a
month-on-month basis, gross sales have been dropping at a reducing
rate."
</P>
<P>
Gross sales in November dropped by about 30 percent over
October. In December sales went down by 16 percent and in January
by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We note that in February, sentiment has improved and in
general investors have a higher propensity to invest. However, we
would not expect sales to rebound immediately," Lord said.
</P>
<P>
The HKIFA consists of 45 fund management companies as
full/overseas members and has about 40 associate members including
trustees and other professionals which are involved in the
creation and administration of funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
