<HEADLINE> Share Prices Up on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed firmer
after an active session on the Singapore market, as the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) rose by 7.39 points to
finish at 1546.05 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that buying was encouraged by the firmer trend in
regional currencies, and especially, the market was buoyed by
optimism that Indonesia would forge a compromise with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Light foreign fund buying helped to lift prices, particularly
those of blue chip stocks, they note.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume increased to 343.87 million units, valued
at 357.58 million Singapore dollars (about 218.04 million US
dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines by 268 to 72, while 273
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 31.71 million units. It was followed by
M. Resources which had 27.72 million shares traded. MBf Capital
was next with 21.01 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
NorBorneo led the gainers of the day as it rose by 46 cents to
finish at 3.92 Singapore dollars. Jurong Shipyard increased by 35
cents to end at 7.9 Singapore dollars, while Gentings was up by 32
cents to close at 4.92 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, local computer sound card maker Creative 50
was the biggest loser as it declined by 1.2 dollars to end at 34.6
Singapore dollars. Asean Fund fell by 70 cents to close at 7.8
Singapore dollars. DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign
lost 40 cents to finish at 12.1 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
