<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Higher as Asian Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar continued
to follow the fortunes of its northern neighbors Tuesday, firming
as Asian currencies began to show signs of strength.
</P>
<P>
The Australian unit finished the local session at 66.82 U.S.
cents, from 66.58 U.S. cents Monday.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank head of foreign exchange Craig Busch said the
Australian dollar traded in a range of 66.58 to 67.00 U.S. cents,
"it has really been chopped around on the fortunes of Asian
currencies."
</P>
<P>
The local currency reached its intraday highs as the Asian
currencies began to firm. "Aussie just followed the Asian
currencies today," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also Indonesian President Soeharto was returned to office for a
seventh term. Indonesian House Speaker Harmoko told an electoral
committee meeting that Soeharto was the only candidate for the
post and declared he will lead the country for the 1998-2003 term.
</P>
<P>
Against the Indonesian rupiah, the U.S. dollar fell to
IDR10,600 from IDR10,900 the previous day.
</P>
<P>
"Dollar/yen came off in the afternoon as well, and that put a
bit of support under the Aussie," Busch said.
</P>
<P>
The local market has recently seen the 66.50 to 66.60 U.S.
cents level hold, and buyers were expected to push the local
currency up to 67.50 U.S. cents on the topside.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Australian dollar closed here at 85.00 yen, down
slightly from 85.26 yen Monday, it was also at 1.2201 marks, up
from 1.2184 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
