<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Repatriates Two Planeloads of Illegal Vietnamese Migrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A group of 274 Vietnamese were
returned by air to Hanoi, Vietnam, on Tuesday, on the 113th and
114 flights under the Orderly Repatriation Program (ORP), the Hong
Kong government announced.
</P>
<P>
Two hundred and forty-eight were deemed illegal immigrants
while 26 considered migrants. The majority of them arrived in Hong
Kong in 1997, with the remaining in 1989, 1990, 1991, 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
The returnees comprise of 220 men, 36 women, 11 boys and seven
girls.
</P>
<P>
The group brought to 11,860 the total number repatriated on 114
ORP flights since October 1991.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Security Bureau showed that since the
emergence of the Vietnamese boat people in 1975, Hong Kong has
received over 200,000 people from Vietnam. Of these, some 143,000
have been resettled in third countries and over 69,000 returned
to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
But the Special Administrative Region (SAR) government is still
working hard in negotiating with the Vietnamese government so that
the problem of the Vietnamese boat people would be solved as soon
as possible, said the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government announced in January this year the scrapping
of the port of first asylum policy, imposed on Hong Kong by the
British Government in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The abolition meant that there would be no more special
treatment to illegal Vietnamese arrivals in Hong Kong in future.
They would be treated in the same way as are illegal arrivals from
any other country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
