<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stomach Illnesses Increase In U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Stomach illnesses caused by
food are on the rise in the United States, a leading scientist
told the on-going International Conference on Emerging Infectious
Diseases in Atlanta Monday.
</P>
<P>
"After all the years we have spent improving our food supply,
it appears the problem of stomach illness has increased," said
Michael Osterholm, Minnesota's state epidemiologist, at the
conference which began Sunday and runs through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Scientists found an average of one stomach illness per person
annually in a study of 86 families conducted in Cleveland between
1948 and 1957. But in the last two years, studies in five places
around the United States have found a rate of 1.4 illnesses per
person annually. In Minnesota, the rate is 1.8, said Osterholm.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rise to two possible reasons. The first is
that almost half the money Americans set aside for food is spent
in cafes and restaurants, where diners are vulnerable to the
safety practices of workers who are young and poorly paid and may
not wash their hands, Osterholm said.
</P>
<P>
The other is the push to eat more fresh fruits and vegetables
all year round, which forces the United States to import more
products from other countries with less stringent cleanliness
standards, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that in 1996 more than a third of all
cantaloupes, 74 percent of green onions and 79 percent of
cucumbers were imported from Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plenary Meeting of Ninth NPC Session Hears Reports () </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The third plenary meeting of the
First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) this
afternoon heard reports on the work of the Eighth NPC Standing
Committee, the Supreme People's Court and the Supreme People's
Procuratorate, and passed a Decision on the Plan Concerning
Institutional Restructuring of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
According to the Decision on the Plan Concerning Institutional
Restructuring of the State Council, the Ninth NPC First Session
heard explanations on the plan made by State Councillor and
Secretary-General of the State Council Luo Gan, deliberated the
plan and decided to approve the plan.
</P>
<P>
The plenary meeting, presided over by Wu Jieping, an executive
chairman of the presidium of the Ninth NPC First Session, also
approved election and appointment methods for the Ninth NPC
First Session.
</P>
<P>
Eighth NPC Standing Committee Vice-Chairman Tian Jiyun, Supreme
People's Court President Ren Jianxin and Supreme People's
Procuratorate Procurator-General Zhang Siqing delivered reports at
the plenary meeting.
</P>
<P>
Tian Jiyun said in his report that the Eighth NPC Standing
Committee has focused on improving socialist democracy and the
country's legal system, adhered to and improved the people's
congress system, and conscientiously performed its
responsibilities provided for by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee has made marked achievements in
legislation, especially legislation on economic affairs, improved
and strengthened supervision, promoted the process of building a
socialist country ruled by law, and guaranteed smooth progress in
reform, opening-up and the modernization drive, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
During their tenure of office, the Eighth NPC and its Standing
Committee deliberated 129 draft laws and law-related draft
decisions, and enacted 85 laws and 33 law-related decisions.
</P>
<P>
"A large number of laws have been enacted with their quality
improved," Tian said, noting that "the laws have laid a foundation
for a socialist legal system with Chinese characteristics."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plenary Meeting of Ninth NPC Session Hears Reports (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To supervise the implementation of the Constitution and other
laws and to supervise the State Council, the Supreme People's
Court and the Supreme People's Procuratorate is an important power
given to the National People's Congress and its Standing Congress
by the Constitution, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the process of developing a socialist market economy, such
supervisions should be strengthened," Tian Jiyun said.
</P>
<P>
He said that over the past five years, the Standing Committee
has continued to give the same emphasis on examination of and
supervision over law enforcement as on legislation.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the Standing Committee has examined the
implementation of 21 laws and law-related decisions, and the
special committees of the NPC have conducted examinations on the
enforcement of relevant laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jianxin, president of the Supreme People's Court, said that
over the past five years, courts at various levels have followed
the guiding thinking of serving reform, opening-up and socialist
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Focusing on the basic tasks of guaranteeing reform, promoting
development and safeguarding modernization, the courts have
strengthened judicial work in an all-round way according to the
Constitution and other laws, Ren said.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1997, courts throughout China completed more than
22.4 million first-ruling criminal, civil, economic,
administrative and marine cases, recording an annual increase of
11.47 percent, with claims involved rising year by year, which
amounted to a total of 951.5 billion yuan in five years.
</P>
<P>
The people's courts have made persevering efforts to crack down
on criminal offenses, while putting emphasis on punishing such
crimes as corruption and bribery committed by officials in Party
and government leading organs, and administrative, law-enforcement,
judicial and economic administrative departments.
</P>
<P>
In the five years, the courts completed more than 2.4 million
first-ruling criminal cases. Court verdicts involving 2.7 million
persons came into legal effect.
</P>
<P>
Those who were sentenced to more than five years in prison,
life in prison and death (including death with reprieve) accounted
for 40.08 percent of all convicted criminals.
</P>
</TEXT>
