<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, U.S. to Resume Talks on Opening Air Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 10 (Xinhua) -- France and the United States will
resume talks Tuesday in Washington on opening their air markets to
each other, said a French official.
</P>
<P>
During the previous round of talks last month in Paris, the two
sides failed to reach agreement to give free access to their
airports to air companies of the two countries, because of the
French concern that unbridled competition from American air
companies could damage Air France.
</P>
<P>
But the French Foreign Ministry estimated that an agreement is
possible.
</P>
<P>
Air France is now prevented from carrying out its already
signed cooperation programs with U.S. companies of Delta and
Continental because of the absence of an open space agreement
between France and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The United States has already signed open space agreements with
a number of European nations, including Germany, the Netherlands,
Belgium and Austria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
