<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Procuratorial Bodies Play Active Role (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Procuratorial bodies at all
levels across China have played an active role in combating
corruption, severely cracking down on major crimes and
safeguarding judicial justice and a unified legal system.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made here today by Zhang Siqing,
procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate, in a
work report he delivered at the third meeting of the First Session
of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that, regarding anti-corruption as one of their
major duties, procuratorial bodies at all levels have spearheaded
their strikes against criminal offences involving Party and
government departments, administrative and law enforcement bodies,
judicial organs and economic administrative departments,
especially those involving officials above the county level.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1997, he said, procuratorial bodies across the
country investigated 387,352 cases of power abuse, including
embezzlement, bribery, dereliction of duty and infringement on
citizens' personal and democratic rights.
</P>
<P>
The investigations helped retrieve direct economic losses worth
22.92 billion yuan (about 2.8 billion US dollars) for the state,
and legal proceedings were taken against 181,873 people involved
in such cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
The procuratorial bodies also received an increasing number of
tips on power abuse cases from the general public, and the number
of tips that led to investigations totaled more than 1.8 million
in the past five years, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that procuratorial bodies at all levels have always
taken it as a major political task to maintain stability, and have
closely cooperated with public and state security bodies, courts
and departments of justice and administration to severely crack
down on crimes seriously harming public security.
</P>
<P>
"In the past five years, procuratorial bodies across the
country examined 2,004,785 arrest warrant applications involving
3,344,709 people submitted by the public and state security
departments, and issued 1,779,494 arrest warrants involving
2,893,771 people," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
