<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Prices Boosted by Snow, Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Prices for grain and soybean
futures increased lightly Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade as
heavy snow and rain swept across North and South Americas.
</P>
<P>
In early trading, wheat for May delivery was 4.5 cents higher
at 3.39 U.S. dollars a bushel.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say wheat futures were boosted by concerns that the
cold and snow that swept across U.S. Midwest Monday morning will
adversely affect the winter wheat crop.
</P>
<P>
Corn futures were boosted by news that heavy rains fell over
the weekend in Argentina, where the harvest of a large corn crop
is getting under way, they said.
</P>
<P>
One reason behind the higher prices for soybean futures, they
believe, is coming from the fears that bad weather will delay the
harvest of Brazil's soybean crop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
