<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Achieves Big Drop in Trade Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Israel's trade deficit in 1997
fell to 3.6 billion U.S. dollars from 5.3 billion dollars in 1996,
registering a 32.1 percent plunge, the Haaretz daily reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics has attributed the
decline of the trade deficit mainly to an increase in exports, the
daily said.
</P>
<P>
Figures have shown that Israel sold 32 billion dollars worth of
goods and services last year, 1.5 billion dollars more than those
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It also received a unilateral transfer of 8 billion dollars
last year, witnessing a rise of 200,000 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, its imports of goods and services last year stood
at 43.6 billion dollars, about the same as those in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The shrinking of the trade deficit is a further evidence of an
economic slowdown in Israel, as it indicates that the internal
consumption is slumping.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman and State Budget
Director David Milgrom will announce plans later this week to
promote the recovery of the national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
