<HEADLINE> China's Top Judge Calling for Continued Crack-Down on Crimes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the past five years, the scope of civil affairs cases
subjected to trial have been increased steadily with a number of
disputes involving properties increasing remarkably, and there is
somewhat a change in the type of civil cases. Consequently, the
number of criminal cases increased with each passing year.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, people's courts in China have handled
13.5 million first-ruling civil cases, at an average annual growth
rate of 10.72 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the number of economic cases has been on the
rise, with the emergence of new-type cases, filtrating into the
economic spheres and new and high-tech fields. The amount of
claimed funds totalled 937 billion yuan in the past five years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
To further increase the protection of the intellectual
right the Supreme people's courts and some higher and intermediate
people's courts have set up their own intellectual tribunals and
formed a contingent of judges. They have settled a total of 16,894
cases covering patent, trademark and copy rights, representing an
average annual rate of 5.83 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that intellectual achievements have won respect
from the whole society and been protected by law, he added.
</P>
<P>
The number of cases involving foreign nationals also grow year
by year. People's courts in the country completed 19,074 such
first ruling cases in the five-year period, up 14.57 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
Administrative cases involve the acts of unfair law-enforcement
by many administrative departments and, through the handling of
such cases, the rights and interests of citizens were protected
and public security and administrative organs were guaranteed to
perform their duties in accordance with law, Ren said.
</P>
<P>
Establishing a compensation system constitute a new trend in
development of socialist democracy and legality. All people's
courts at or above the intermediate level have set up their
compensation committees since the "Compensation Law" was put into
effect in 1995.
</P>
