<HEADLINE> China's Top Judge Calling for Continued Crack-Down on Crimes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- China's top judge Ren Jianxin
said here today that the people's court will unswervingly adhere
to the principle of "striking hard" and give a heavier and quicker
punishment on criminal offenders who jeopardize social security in
accordance with law.
</P>
<P>
A major task for the people's court is to wage a protracted
hard struggle against crimes and create a favorable social
environment for China's socialist modernization drive, said Ren
Jianxin, president of the Supreme People's court, at the third
plenary session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) held
here today.
</P>
<P>
The people's courts across China handled a total of 22.4
million first-instance cases involving criminal offenses,
civilian, economic, administrative and marine affairs in the
1993-97 period, with an annual recored growth rate of 11.47
percentm and a total of 951.5 billion yuan claimed in these
lawsuits over the past five years, Ren said.
</P>
<P>
The number of first-ruling criminal cases concluded amounted to
2.4 million, posting a yearly increase of 0.75 percent. Some 2.7
million court verdicts were passed, he noted. A direct economic
loss of 26.5 billion yuan was retrieved for the state and
collective units.
</P>
<P>
The people's courts in China have taken the crackdown on
corruption and bribery as its major tasks in fighting corruption,
building a clean and government and providing a direct service for
the reform, opening-up and economic construction. They have made
particularly hard efforts to deal with such crimes as corruption,
bribery, embezzlement of public funds and fraudulent practices in
Party and government leading bodies and government administrative,
law-enforcing, judicial and economic management departments.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,610 officials at and above the county or division
level were sentenced, in which 171 were officials at departmental
(bureau) level and five others at the provincial or ministerial
level, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Top Judge Calling for Continued Crack-Down on Crimes (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the past three years, the people's courts across China
have handled 870 such cases, 364 of which were paid by government
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Whether written judgement and other law documents can be
implemented has a direct bearing on the dignity of state laws and
materialization of lawful rights and interests of the parties
involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6.689 million cases other than criminal ones were
concluded with a sum of 268.5 billion yuan claimed in the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
People's courts at all levels have been attaching great
importance to supervision over adjudication, and unfair or
erroneous verdicts will be firmed corrected in accordance with
law, Ren said.
</P>
<P>
They received 3.38 million visits or letters of complaints
lodged by people in all parts of the country in the past five
years and gave 20.56 million replies. People's courts examined
complaints and petitions in real earnest, promptly filed cases in
accordance with law or set forth for re-trial if necessary, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, people's courts have implemented a
series of reforms including those in public trial, enhancing of
the courts' functions, and opening public investigations, debates
and cross-examinations in to bid to subjected court trial under
the supervision of the masses of people. Moreover, China has
formulated and promulgated the Law on Judges.
</P>
<P>
The people's courts have earnestly investigated and punished
those acts in violation of laws and disciplines.
</P>
<P>
However, Ren stated, there still exist many weakpoints and
problems, and some of them are serious. In some cases, the law was
not strictly enforced and the verdicts passed by some courts were
unfair. Moreover, protectionism from localities and various
departments have seriously interfered in the court judgment, he
added.
</P>
<P>
And effective measures will be made to solve these problems
with particular measures to be taken to eliminate crimes committed
by those who misuse their powers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Major tasks for 1998 and a longer period to come are to enforce
laws in an earnest manner, go in for reforms in courts and build a
contingent of judges to so as to provide a judicial guarantee for
pushing the cause of socialism with Chinese characteristics into
21st century, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
