<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebel Resume Low-Level Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Peace negotiators of the
Philippine government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) resumed their talks in Sultan Kudarat, the southern
province of Maguindanao, on Tuesday, the Philippine News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chair for political affairs, was
quoted by the report as saying that the meeting which is scheduled
for three days will tackle issues regarding the setting of the
venue, date and agenda of the formal talks.
</P>
<P>
The peace panels will also discuss the identification of MILF's
controlled territories in southern Philippines, including its 30
major camps in Mindanao, he said.
</P>
<P>
The negotiators will hear a report of Eliseo Mercado, chairman
of the Independent Fact Finding Committee and the newly created
Quick Reaction Team, regarding the result of the two independent
bodies' special meeting held on March 3.
</P>
<P>
The reaction team is a monitoring body recently created by the
negotiation panels to resolve conflicts between government troops
and the rebels while the peace process is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
It is composed of six representatives from the government, six
from the MILF and another six from the fact finding committee.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction from the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF) and now the largest Muslim rebel group, refuses to be
included in the peace accord signed between the government and
MNLF and wants its own peace agreement with Manila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
