<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Crisis' Impact on Growth Serious: ADB President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis is
producing serious consequences for the economic growth in the
region over the next few years, but the region still has the
strong foundation for recovery, Asian Development Bank (ADB)
President Mitsuo Sato said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Opening a senior policy seminar on Managing Global Financial
Integration in Asia, Sato said that the consequences of the crisis
for growth in Asia over the next few years are serious and several
countries will experience negative economic growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Depending on how quickly and decisively (the) economies act,
some recovery may occur in 1999," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Social costs of this recession will also be very large.
Inflation rates, unemployment, and poverty levels will be high.
Indeed, as a direct result of what is happening in Asia, there
will be slower global growth this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
But, Sato said, over the medium term and a longer term, growth
recovery will depend on the determination with which Asia tackles
underlying institutional, governance, and structural problems.
</P>
<P>
There are grounds for optimism that bold steps necessary to
rehabilitate and strengthen economies will be taken, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Once this challenge has met, the strong foundations that have
propelled growth in the past should once again come to the fore,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day seminar, the participants will discuss
emerging lessons and prospective challenges of globalization for
the region.
</P>
<P>
High level officials from 12 ADB Members, the private sector
and multilateral agencies are attending the meeting, which was
jointly sponsored by the World Bank and the ADB.
</P>
<P>
Other topics for discussion are perspectives and implications
of the current (Asian financial) crisis, challenges for
macro-economic management in an integrated environment, dealing
with financial distress and capital markets reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
