<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal Profession Becoming More Attractive to Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The yearly application process
for taking the lawyers' qualification examination is still three
months away. And yet many Chinese between 20 and 40 are rushing to
buy guidance materials and sign up for preparation schools.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, more than 500,000 people have taken the
exam, though less than one fifth have passed it. However,
increasing number of people have passed the exam year by year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Lawyers Department under the Chinese
Ministry of Justice earlier this week told Xinhua that the legal
profession has become an admirable one to many Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"Now lawyers are playing an increasingly important role in
China as a result of improvements in the country's legal system
and the development of the market economy," the official said,
adding that these are the main reasons why becoming a lawyer is
more attractive.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, in the past five years Chinese
lawyers served as legal consultants to more than 250,000 work
units and participated in the handling of nearly seven million
criminal and civil cases or disputes.
</P>
<P>
"Lawyers in China also have provided good legal services to
various key national construction projects like the Three Gorges
Dam Project and the Shanghai Metro Project, contributing greatly
to the smooth operation of these projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the official said, the role played by lawyers has
drawn more attention in such sectors as finance, securities, real
estate, intellectual property rights, international trade and the
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
The official estimated that by the end of this century, there
will be 150,000 Chinese lawyers. The figure will reach
250,000-to-300,000 by 2010.
</P>
<P>
"Lawyers in China may find more roles to play in the future, as
the 'rule by law' principle is being more and more respected and
the nation's market-oriented reform is deepened," the official
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
