<HEADLINE> Manila to Host Regional Meeting on Transnational Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
host the Asia-Pacific Regional Ministerial Meeting on
Transnational Crime in Manila from March 23 to 25.
</P>
<P>
The decision to host the meeting showed the government's
reaffirmation of its commitment to combating transnational
organized crimes, Secretary of Department of Interior and Local
Governments Epimaco Velasco said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, interior and home affairs ministers from 50
countries in the Asia-Pacific region and 150 other participants
will discuss measures on how to combat transnational organized
crime syndicates whose illegal activities include money
laundering, drug trafficking and firearms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
"Leaders of these countries are now taking serious cognizance
of the threat posed by transnational crimes to the socio-political
and economic stability of their respective nations," Velasco said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said that the objective of the ministerial meeting is to
provide a forum by which nations can plan a concerted global
effort to combat crimes which have become a menace worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"Transnational crimes recognize no boundaries, religion,
ideologies and race. They wreak havoc on the people and their
countries," he said, adding that the best approach to combat them
is through a unified and well-coordinated plan of action among
nations.
</P>
<P>
Among the expected output of the meeting is a "Manila
Declaration on the Prevention and Control of Organized Crime and
Corruption," which is to be signed and approved by the 50 interior
and home affairs ministers by the end of the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, participating countries will also each
present a technical paper detailing the state of peace and order
in their countries and the efforts made in the campaign against
transnational crimes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Undersecretary for Local Governments Manuel Sanchez
said the three-day meeting is a wider follow-up to the ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Conference on
Transnational Crimes which the Philippines hosted and sponsored
last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
