<HEADLINE> Lebanon's National Carrier Strives for Curbing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's national carrier Middle
East Airline (MEA) has announced a plan to curb losses, the
Lebanese Daily Star newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The airline will achieve its goals by canceling unprofitable
flights and increasing the frequency of the remaining, Mohammed
Hout, MEA's chairman of board of directors, told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
"By increasing worldwide connections, and making efficient use
of resources, planes and employees, the company will save 20
million U.S. dollars (in a year)," he was quoted by the Daily Star
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The national carrier witnessed a loss of 53 million dollars
last year, Hout said, adding that this is a proof that the old
flight network, designed for Lebanese expatriate travel, is no
longer appropriate.
</P>
<P>
The airlines will suspend eight unprofitable services by June 1
and concentrate its activities on more promising markets.
</P>
<P>
To suspend some of the flights does not mean less activity of
MEA, instead, it will have a 26 percent increase in weekly flights
and a 46 percent rise in using its aircraft, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that MEA will form four subsidiary companies,
including one for airport maintenance and service which began to
operate on March 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
