<HEADLINE> Refugees in Tanzania Plant Crops to Feed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,500 refugees in a
refugee camp in west Tanzania's Tabora Region have started to
plant crops to feed themselves rather than wait for relief
supplies, a member of parliament has said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees at Kigwa camp have cultivated 2,000 hectares of
agricultural crops setting a good example of farming at Igalula
Ward in Tabora rural areas, the member of parliament for Igalula
constituency, Tatu Ntimizi, told the Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
Refugees from eight countries have planted maize, beans for
food and cash crops like tobacco, sunflower for profit so as to
reduce reliance on food supplies from the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and other relief agencies, she
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The MP said the refugees are from the Democratic Republic of
Congo, Rwanda, Burundi, the Sudan, Kenya, Angola, Uganda and
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
"The refugees have shown that agriculture is the mainstay of
any person, and have set a good example for other people living
in the constituency," Ntimizi was quoted by the newspaper as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains this year, however, have destroyed up to 3,200
hectares of various crops in Igalula alone. Assistance of 100
tons of food and medicine is required for over 600 people
surrounded by water in the ward, she said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Tanzania plays host to about 340,000 refugees,
UNHCR statistics indicated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
