<HEADLINE> Bush Fires Destroy Vegetation in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Bush fires destroyed 400 square
kilometers of vegetation in a national park in northeastern
Uganda, "The New Vision" reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Aleper, the acting chief park warden of Kidepo National
Park in Kotido District, said 120 people including army men
deployed there failed to put out the fires and that one third of
the park has been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The national park lacks of mechanical fire-fighting equipment,
he told the paper.
</P>
<P>
The fires have destroyed the Lolamat Circuit on the eastern
side of the park, he added.
</P>
<P>
The fires may be caused by poachers, he derived. Poachers use
fire to roast meat or to drive out wildlife from caves or tall
grass, he narrated. 
