<HEADLINE> Australia Ranks Second in World Car Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Australians are the second most
frequent victims of motor vehicle theft in the world behind the
United Kingdom, according to figures to be presented at a
conference here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian national conference of the International
Association of Auto Theft Investigations (IAATI) will discuss ways
of fighting and reducing car theft in Australia.
</P>
<P>
NRMA (a car insurance company) investigations manager Kieran
Gavin, who represents the Australian chapter of IAATI, said in a
statement released Tuesday that more than 122,000 vehicles were
stolen in Australia in 1996, a 9.3-percent rise since 1993.
</P>
<P>
This was a rate of 11 vehicles for every 1,000 registered.
</P>
<P>
"These rates place Australia second behind the UK in relation
to motor vehicle theft," Gavin said.
</P>
<P>
Recent estimates put the cost to insurance companies at around
650 million Australian dollars (442 million U.S. dollars) a year,
which was returned to the community in higher premium costs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, car theft has a major economic impact, in addition to
the inconvenience and upset for the victims of such crime," he
said.
</P>
<P>
An earlier figure from the Australian Bureau of Statistics
showed that 75 percent of car theft was opportunistic and 25
percent professional.
</P>
<P>
The most common locations are streets and footpaths (37
percent), garages and driveways (18 percent) and car parks (16
percent).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
