<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Manchurian Tigers Believed in Changbai Mountains (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Hu Shaofeng, another official from the Jilin
Provincial Forestry Bureau, during the Chinese Lunar New Year
traces of Manchurian tigers were found in Jiaohe city. The
sighting was confirmed by provincial experts.
</P>
<P>
Manchurian tiger is a large-size meat-eater mainly inhabiting
Russia's Siberian area and the northeastern part of China. China
is believed to have fewer than 20 Manchurian tigers because of the
loss of forests and hunting.
</P>
<P>
Huichun is located in the Tumen River delta area, part of the
Changbai Mountain area and neighboring Russian. Though it does not
belong to the Changbai Mountains Nature Reserve, the city's dense
forests provide a favorable environment for Manchurian tigers to
reside. There have been numerous reports of wild tigers in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Deshan, deputy director of the Huichun City Forestry
Bureau, said that nine cows have been eaten by tigers since August
of 1997, when a 400-kilogram cow was attacked and eaten up on
Naozigou village's pastureland in Madida Township. Local experts
and experienced villagers confirmed the attacks on domestic cattle
were by Manchurian tigers.
</P>
<P>
On Jan. 15, another villager met with a Manchurian tiger on his
way to work and escaped by luck.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Zhengjie from the provincial academy of forestry said
that, since a ban on hunting in the Changbai Mountains went into
effect decades ago, the number of wild animals including wild deer
and boar has increased rapidly, which would provide plenty of food
for tigers.
</P>
<P>
However, cattle are easy prey for tigers.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the protection of wild animals, local
governments have also passed regulations to compensate farmers who
suffer losses from the endangered species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0196 </DOCNO>
