<HEADLINE> Chen Xitong to be Prosecuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Chen Xitong, a former secretary
of the Beijing Municipal Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), will be prosecuted soon on charges of embezzlement of
public funds and dereliction of duty following the end of
investigations into his case.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors began investigations into Chen's case in accordance
with law from September, 1997.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Zhang Siqing, procurator-general of the
Supreme People's Procuratorate, when he delivered a work report at
the annual session of the National People's Congress (NPC), in
session here since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Investigations into and prosecution of serious cases of
embezzlement, bribe taking and dereliction of duty, especially
those involving leading officials, indicate that China's
anti-corruption campaign has intensified," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, when China launched a new round of anti-corruption
campaign, procuratorates at all levels have been dealing with
crimes committed in Party and government organizations, and
administrative, law-enforcement, judicial and economic
administrative departments, crimes involving officials above the
county level in particular, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, procuratorates at all levels have
prosecuted a total of 180,000 people on charges of bribe taking,
embezzlement of public funds and dereliction of duty, among whom,
2,903 are county-level officials, 265 prefecture-level officials
and seven ministerial-level officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
