<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Tourism Hit by Asian Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Australia's tourism industry is
hit hard by the Asian economic crisis with official statistics
predicting a 5-percent fall in international visitor number this
year.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the tourism industry met with government ministers
here Tuesday to discuss the impact of the Asian economic crisis
and their call for a reinvestment package.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Council of Australia (TCA) said in a statement that
the 5-percent drop means an 800 million Australian dollar (536
million U.S. dollars) cut in earnings and 216,000 fewer people
visiting Australia.
</P>
<P>
TCA Managing Director Bruce Baird said in the statement, "The
Australian tourism industry is at a crossroads and in need of
strategic reinvestment to develop new markets, drive growth from
traditional markets and maximize the tourism advantage from Sydney
2000."
</P>
<P>
"As the nation's major employer, providing one in nine jobs, it
is essential to develop strategies that boost the industry."
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Andrew Thomson said that while there has been
a downturn from some key Asian markets, "the government, through
the Australian Tourist Commission, is running major new campaigns
to bolster traditional, high-yield markets such as the United
States, the United Kingdom and Japan."
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's meeting, which involves Trade Minister Tim Fischer
and Industry Minister John Moore, would also provide worthwhile
input into the National Action Plan for Tourism, soon to be
presented to the cabinet, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Season Arrives Early on Middle Reaches of Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The flood season has started one
month earlier than usual on the Xiangjiang and Zijiang rivers,
both branches of the Yangtze River, China's longest.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain since March 6 has brought the earliest flooding to
the Hunan Province region recorded since 1910.
</P>
<P>
Hunan water officials said flood peaks at various monitoring
points range from 2.2-to-5.9 meters higher than the alarm
level. This kind of flooding occurs once every 5-to-10 years.
</P>
<P>
Since last winter, there has been more rain than usual in Hunan
Province. The water levels of the Xiangjiang, Zijiang, Yuanjiang,
Lishui rivers -- the four major branches of the Yangtze in the
middle reaches -- and Dongting Lake are 2-to-3 meters higher than
normal.
</P>
<P>
Officials said Hunan was unprepared for the early, sudden and
violent flooding. Anti-flood and water conservation projects under
way were not scheduled for completion until just before the
traditional flood season.
</P>
<P>
The province had to release some water from major reservoirs
along the Xiangjiang and Zijiang rivers.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has issued urgent circulars calling
for "an immediate readiness for the battle against floods."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Strongly Confident in Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of
China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), Monday
told the German businessmen that he has strong confidence in the
future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a dinner party hosted by German business leaders at
the Association of German Chambers of Industry and Commerce
(DIHT), Tung attributed his confidence above all to the
implementation of late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping's idea of "one
country, two systems" which gives Hong Kong a high degree of
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Tung, on his first official visit to Germany after Hong Kong's
return to China last July, also stressed that despite the
financial turmoil affecting Southeast Asia, Hong Kong is capable
of maintaining its competitiveness without the devaluation of the
Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong needs not to devaluate its currency in order to
compete, Tung said, thanks to its 98 billion U.S. dollar foreign
exchange reserve, the third highest in the world, as well as
advantages that other Asian countries do not have.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's service sector turnout accounts for 85 percent of
Hong Kong's gross domestic product (GDP), he said, plus predicable
policies, low taxes as well as the rule of law in the area.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hong Kong, which boasts healthy economic structure
and well-regulated financial markets, is free of the macroeconomic
policy faults as the Asian countries hardest hit by the financial
turmoil have.
</P>
<P>
Tung reiterated that Hong Kong will stick to its 14-year-old
linked exchange rates, which the latest polls show are supported by
70 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
The position has received strong support from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and if necessary, will also get financial
support from mainland China, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Tung, Hong Kong is not only defending its
currency, it is also planning to invest massively in the near
future in education, housing, transport and information technology.
</P>
<P>
In answering a question, Tung expressed the strong belief that
the Chinese currency Renminbi will not devaluate, just as Chinese
leaders have stated.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the dinner party, Juegen Heraeus, chairman
of the China working group of the Asian-Pacific Committee of the
German Economy, praised the efforts by the central government of
China and the local government of Hong Kong to maintain the value
of RMB and Hong Kong dollar, which has served as the stability
anchor in the financial markets in Asia.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that China, including Hong Kong,
will make efforts in order to launch an energetic new start for
economic growth in Asia as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
