<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Manchurian Tigers Believed in Changbai Mountains (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations investigation
team claim they have found traces of three-to-five wild Manchurian
tigers in the forests near Huichun, a city in northeast China's
Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
The finding confirms local reports that nine cows had been
eaten by tigers in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
Manchurian tigers have been considered on the verge of
extinction for decades in northeast China, their original home.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. delegation, formed by four Russian experts and one
from the United States, has completed an eight-day investigation
on wild Manchurian tigers in the forests of Huichun near the
Changbai Mountains.
</P>
<P>
During their investigation, the U.N. team found tiger prints on
the snow-covered ground along with their excrement, resting places
and bones of other animals they had eaten.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Jilin Provincial Forestry Bureau, who is
accompanying the delegation, quoted the delegation members as
saying the the group of Manchurian tigers near Huichun probably
includes at least one tigress.
</P>
<P>
A Russian expert reportedly said this is a different species of
tigers from those discovered in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program (UNDP) began
investigating Manchurian tigers two years ago. They completed
their investigation in Russia amd were continuing their studies in
northeast China this year. The aim of the investigation is to make
clear the number of Manchurian tigers and to take effective
measures to protect them.
</P>
<P>
The investigation is still under way in Jilin province's
Wangqing County, some 70 kilometers away from Huichun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0211 </DOCNO>
