<HEADLINE> China's Election System Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth National People's
Congress (NPC) and its standing committee have improved China's
election system and made the process of election more democratic
by enacting and amending election laws, a leading legislator said
here today.
</P>
<P>
During the term of the Eighth NPC, two change-of-term elections
were held, one for people's congresses at the township level, and
the other for local people's congresses at the county level and
above and for the NPC, said Tian Jiyun, a vice-chairman of the
Eighth NPC Standing Committee, at the third meeting of the Ninth
NPC First Session held here today.
</P>
<P>
The Eighth NPC Standing Committee also took charge of the
election of deputies to the Ninth NPC in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR). In accordance with the method of
election for NPC deputies to the Ninth NPC in the HKSAR adopted by
the NPC, it approved a list of members for an Electoral College of
the HKSAR. And election was conducted in accordance with law.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time for Hong Kong to elect its own NPC
deputies to the highest organ of state power as an independent
electoral body since it returned to the embrace of the motherland.
It is an important symbol of Chinese citizens among Hong Kong
residents having a say in state affairs as masters of their
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Change-of-term elections are an important democratic process in
which the entire people participate, he said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to law violations in elections, the NPC Standing
Committee instructed relevant departments and localities to make
immediate corrections and deal with violators severely, thereby
ensuring smooth elections, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
