<HEADLINE> Snowstorm Strikes U.S. Midwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- A spring snowstorm lashed the
Midwest of the United States Monday, closing highways and airports
and knocking out electricity to more than 400,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
About 30 centimeters of snow fell in Wisconsin, Illinois and
northwestern Indiana Monday while heavy snowfalls over the weekend
in central Iowa were heaped into 3-meter snowdrifts in the state's
capital city of Des Moines by wind.
</P>
<P>
Five traffic deaths in Missouri, two in Kansas and one in
Wisconsin were blamed on the weather, according to an Associated
Press report.
</P>
<P>
After a mild winter because of the El Nino, wind chills had
dropped below zero in Iowa and North Dakota Monday.
</P>
<P>
Blizzard conditions at O'Hare International Airport in Chicago,
the world's busiest passenger airport, reduced arrivals and
departures to just 20 percent of normal, backing up flights
elsewhere around the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indiana shut down southbound Interstate 65 because
of drifting snow. A section of 440 kilometers of highway in
Nebraska has also been shut down since Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The snowstorm has disrupted normal life in some areas. In
Illinois, About 275,000 homes and businesses were without power.
Some 30,000 customers in Wisconsin and 135,000 in northern Indiana
were also blacked out.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, tornadoes damaged retirement communities,
mobile home parks and campgrounds in Florida, and flooding forced
some 2,000 people to flee their homes in southern Alabama.
</P>
<P>
Nine deaths had been blamed on the flooding and tornadoes
across the Southeast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
