<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paintings of Austrian Artist Max Weiler on Display in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-one representative
paintings of Austrian artist Max Weiler went on display in the
China Art Gallery here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and his
Austrian counterpart, Wolfgang Schuessel, attended the opening and
ribbon-cutting ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel addressed the opening ceremony, saying that it is
Austria's honor to present Weiler's works as part of the '98 China
Year of International Fine Arts (CYIFA) series.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will further enhance cultural exchanges between
Austria and China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel praised the cultural contacts in music, opera and
fine arts between the two countries in recent years, and cited
such cooperation as "milestones in the development of friendly and
fruitful relations."
</P>
<P>
Born in 1910, Weiler is one of the most famous modern painters
in Austria.
</P>
<P>
Exhibiting works in China has long been a cherished wish of
Weiler, 88, who identified himself with principles he found in
Chinese landscape painting of the Song Dynasty (960-1279).
</P>
<P>
The artist combined the Chinese style with modern European
abstract art and created stylish, heart-touching paintings.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition was organized by China's Ministry of Culture and
the Austrian Foreign Ministry and presented by the China
International Exhibition Agency and the China Art Gallery.
</P>
<P>
The works on display, mainly from the Vienna Art History Museum
and private collections from other countries, are considered among
his best.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
