<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Beijing Residents Investing in Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The number of Beijing stock
investors has surged in recent years, indicating that residents of
the Chinese capital are becoming increasingly aware of financial
risks.
</P>
<P>
The number of stock-trading accounts in Beijing has soared by
an average 137 percent each year since the market was opened
in 1993, hitting 1.11 million by the end of last year. Of the
accounts, 99.5 percent have been opened by individual investors.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors in the Chinese capital opened 2,977
stock-trading accounts last year, up 79.6 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rapid growth rate in the number of trading
accounts, there is still great room for further development of the
stock market, which was started years after those in the major
coastal cities in the east and south, experts say.
</P>
<P>
They expect another 600,000 stock-trading accounts to be opened
in Beijing this year.
</P>
<P>
China's stock market was opened in the early 1990s when two
stock exchanges were set up in Shanghai and the special economic
zone of Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
China now has 757 listed companies and more than 34
million stock investors. The market capitalization of the listed
firms was valued at 1.81 trillion yuan at the end of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
