<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and Figures About Indonesia: 3 Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's highest legal body,
the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), is holding its General
Session to endorse the country's State Policy Guidelines for the
next five years and elected a president Tuesday, and will elect a
vice president on Wednesday. The MPR consists of five factions --
the ruling Golkar Party and its alliance the Armed Force and the
regional representatives, the United Development Party (PPP) as
well as the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI).
</P>
<P>
The following are the profiles of the three parties:
</P>
<P>
-- The United Development Party (PPP), an Islam-oriented group,
was set up in 1973 after merger of four Islamic parties. At the
beginning, the new party bore the symbol of Kaabah, the Muslim
shrine of Saudi Arabia. In 1987, however, the PPP replaced the
symbol with a five-point star.
</P>
<P>
Most of the party's constituents are Ulema and students of
Pesantren (Islamic boarding school) in the rural areas, mainly in
Java.
</P>
<P>
One of the four former parties making up the PPP is Nahdlatul
Ulama (NU), which has some 30 million supporters and is the
country's largest Muslim organization. Struggles for positions
among leaders of the four factions led to the withdrawal of NU
members from the PPP in 1987, thus undermining the party's
position in that year's general election.
</P>
<P>
There is no official information about the size of the party's
membership.
</P>
<P>
The PPP, which is chaired by veteran politician Ismail Hasan
Metareum, won 22.66 percent of the vote in the sixth general
election held in May last year, about six percentage higher than
that of the 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
-- The Golkar, set up by a group of military and civilian
leaders in 1966, was the dominant socio-political force during
President Soeharto's 32 years of administration. It claims a
membership of 36 million out of a population of 202 million in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Its Chairman is Harmoko, the first civilian to hold the
position since it was established.
</P>
<P>
The Golkar, which has won each of the six elections in the
past, won more than 74 percent of the vote in the general election
held in May last year. In 1992, it won 68 percent of the vote. The
party enjoys full backing from the military, government
bureaucracy and leading businessmen.
</P>
<P>
-- the Indonesia Democratic party (PDI) is an alliance of
several Christian and nationalist parties set up in 1973.
</P>
<P>
In its history, the PDI was pockmarked by internal strifes. The
party has become weaker since 1996 when the party's two factions
conflicted.
</P>
<P>
The PDI, which won 15 percent of the votes in the 1992 general
election, claims a membership of 16 million. However, it only
obtained 3.07 percent of the vote in last year's general election.
</P>
<P>
The two small parties have not gotten any ministerial post in
the cabinet since Soeharto became president in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
