<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Province Protecting Consumers' Rights and Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan Province in southwest
China is making progress in protecting consumers' rights and
interests.
</P>
<P>
Consumers' associations at all levels received 42,207
complaints in 1997, and 98.78 percent of them were resolved,
recovering 22.78 million yuan for consumers.
</P>
<P>
The associations gave priority to some "hot spots" or
"headaches" that received the most consumers'
complaints: commodity quality, housing, tourism, medical
treatment, health-care products, means of agricultural production,
fraud in the service sector, exaggerated advertising, interior
decoration and dry cleaning.
</P>
<P>
The associations conducted 4,498 market inspections last year,
and law enforcement departments collected nearly one million yuan
worth in fines and confiscated goods based on information gained
through inspections.
</P>
<P>
On March 15 of last year, Consumers' Day, the province's
consumers' associations organized 35,800 people to participate in
the publicity effort, received on-the-spot 7,867 complaints, and
provided consulting services for more than a million people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
