<HEADLINE> Northern, Western China Reporting Growth of Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Northern and western areas of
China are reporting rapid growth in foreign trade, according to
information released at a commodity fair here.
</P>
<P>
The areas chalked up 16.6 billion U.S. dollars in foreign trade
in 1997, up 17 percent over 1996. Tianjin, a major outlet for
foreign trade with these areas, increased its freight volume for
foreign trade by 18.6 percent last year, according to the
information.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yixuan, a special representative of the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation to Tianjin, said the
northern and western areas are comparatively backward regions
economically, but these areas have made up each other's
deficiencies through increased cooperation, which has led to a
greater degree of opening-up in their economies.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing China Tianjin Export Commodity Fair, which began on
March 8, is a regional fair jointly started by a dozen provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities of northern and western
China. So far, nine similar fairs have ever been held.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 3.09 billion U.S. dollars of export
business deals were struck during the previous eight commodity
fairs, which drew a total attendance of more than 20,000 overseas
business representatives.
</P>
<P>
Such fairs have also increased cooperation among the hosts.
Tianjin has put forward a strategy of linking its economic
development closely with that of the northern and western areas. A
group of cooperative projects are being implemented.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin Port authorities have pledged to improve its computer
network and infrastructure for customs clearance, as well as to
simplify checking procedures to create better conditions for
interior areas to increase their exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Hong Kong's Economic Prospects Are Bright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- For years Hong Kong's economy has
kept growing at an annual rate of about five percent. Affected by
the Asian financial crisis, the government of the HK Special
Administrative Region sets growth for this year at 3.5 percent,
leaving doubts whether the economy can pick up speed again.
</P>
<P>
Some Hong Kong members of the Ninth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), who
are here attending the committee's first annual session, expressed
belief that Hong Kong's future remains promising.
</P>
<P>
The CPPCC members, including noted industrialists, financial
specialists and university professors, said Hong Kong will shake
off the influence of the financial crisis and resume normal
economic growth by relying on its solid economic foundation,
high-quality government and strong economic support from the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
According to Mun Kin-chok, a professor from the Chinese
University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong has nearly 100 billion US
dollars in foreign exchange reserves, an efficient financial system
and a sound supervisory system.
</P>
<P>
Over the past months, the regional government has shown a
strong capability to handle the financial emergency; the
confidence of Hong Kong people in the Hong Kong dollar has not
weakened, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These are Hong Kong's advantages in having continued economic
development," Mun Kin-chok said.
</P>
<P>
Facing the Asian financial crisis, Hong Kong has adhered to the
practice of pegging its currency with the US dollar and dealt with
emergencies in a proper way. On the other hand, Hong Kong plans to
invest more than 230 billion Hong Kong dollars in the next five
years in infrastructure development in an attempt to promote
internal consumption and stimulate economic growth, the professor
said.
</P>
<P>
Chang Ka-mun, director of board of Peregrine Securities (China)
Ltd., said the regional government has invested heavily in
infrastructure such as housing and road construction to raise the
competitiveness of Hong Kong as a financial and trade center in
the Asia-Pacific area.
</P>
<P>
The first fiscal budget announced by the regional government
not long ago shows that Hong Kong has taken flexible measures in
the face of the Asian financial crisis and that Hong Kong is
strong financially and has the ability to handle its finances,
said Ng Chu Lien Fan, chairman of Hong Kong Tung Wui Securities
Co.
</P>
<P>
Hu Fa-kuang, chairman of the Hong Kong Ryoden Electric
Engineering Co. Ltd., said that the momentum of high economic
growth in the mainland will greatly boost economic expansion in
Hong Kong, providing opportunities for Hong Kong businessmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
