<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Replace 350,000 Obsolete Automobiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- China will replace a record
350,000 obsolete automobiles this year, 50,000 more than in 1996
and 1997.
</P>
<P>
An official with the National Automobile Replacement Leading
Group said that a plan has been worked out and will be carried
out.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, 289,000 automobiles will be replaced in
the country's provinces and metropolitan areas, including 176,000
trucks and 44,000-plus cars. In addition, the military will
replace 61,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that expediting China's auto replacements will
assist the growth of the country's auto industry as well as reduce
urban pollution.
</P>
<P>
China's auto production has grown at an annual rate in excess
of 20 percent since 1991, with output currently exceeding 1.2
million.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of vehicles has brought increasingly serious
air pollution problems. A survey shows that more than 50 percent
of many large cities' air pollution comes from auto emissions.
</P>
<P>
China's National Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA) said
that battling urban auto pollution has become a major focus of the
country's environmental effort.
</P>
<P>
A NEPA official said China will check trucks annually and ban
those with serious pollution problems as well as worn-out city
buses. In addition, some relevant ministries have passed strict
regulations on scrapping worn-out automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that Shanghai plans to replace 2,000 buses with
new ones in the next two years. Some experts in Beijing have also
proposed developing natural-gas-fueled autos to curb the city's
serious air pollution.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 4,000 natural-gas-fueled autos on the road
which are all considered in good operation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Province To Increase Overseas-Funded Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province plans to increase the number of areas open to overseas
investment and improve existing overseas-funded businesses and
investment conditions.
</P>
<P>
An increasing amount of overseas investment is going to
banking, insurance, stocks, accounting, the law, and travel
services and priority will be given to transforming state-owned
enterprises, especially improving technology and management.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors are encouraged to fund infrastructure
construction in energy, transportation, communications,
agriculture, and hi-tech development and emphasis will be placed
on electronics, communications equipment, household appliances,
electrical machinery, petrochemicals and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
An effort will be also be made to improve traditional
industries like textiles, garments, foodstuff, beverages, and
building materials.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had used 81.1 billion US
dollars worth of overseas investment, accounting for 36.6 percent
of the country's total, and 50.1 percent of local exports or 36.3
billion US dollars worth of exports, were from overseas-funded
businesses. 
</P>
