<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Top Legislature Scores Marked Progress in Law-Making (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Senior legislator Tian Jiyun said
today that the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) and its
Standing Committee accelerated the pace of legislation and enacted
laws for the all sectors of socialist market economy over the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
"A large number of laws have been passed with their quality
improved," he said, noting that "the laws have laid a foundation
for a socialist legal system with Chinese characteristics."
</P>
<P>
Tian, vice-chairman of the Eighth NPC Standing Committee, made
the remarks while delivering a report on the work of the Eighth
NPC Standing Committee at the third plenary meeting of the First
Session of the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
During their tenure of office, the Eighth NPC and its Standing
Committee deliberated a total of 129 draft laws and decisions on
the certain law issues, passed 85 laws and 33 decisions on certain
laws, and approved 60 bilateral and multi-lateral international
treaties, conventions and importment agreements, Tian Jiyun said.
</P>
<P>
The amendment to the Constitution passed at the First Session
of the Eighth NPC incorporated the following contents into the
Constitution: "China is in the primary stage of socialism", "the
theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics", and
"the adherence to reform and opening to the outside world."
</P>
<P>
The guilding status for the theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics was established in the form of the
fundamental law of the country.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee designated the acceleration of
economic legislation as its primary task and, centered on the main
links of market oriented economic setup, striving to construct a
legal system framework for the socialist market economy, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the revision and improvement on the Law of Criminal
Procedures and Criminal Law constituted a major event in China's
socialist legislation, and a batch of major laws were formulated
and revised, concerning such spheres as the development of
socialist democracy and politics, education, science, health,
physical culture, environmental protection and national defense.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the vacancy of laws was filled up in some areas,
and contents in the legal system enriched, so that the country's
political and social life has further embarked on the track of
legalization, Tian Jiyun said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Top Legislature Scores Marked Progress in Law-Making (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In accordance with the basic policy of "one country, two
systems" and the specifications in the Basic Law of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), the Standing Committee
drafted the Law on Stationing Troops in the Hong Kong SAR, and
some other relevant laws and decisions.
</P>
<P>
the Standing Committee set up the Preliminary Committee of the
Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong SAR, and the Preparatory
Committee of the Hong Kong SAR according to law.
</P>
<P>
"All this has played an important role in ensuring Hong Kong's
smooth transfer and its prosperity and stability," Tian said.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee has been paying attention to making laws
in accordance with the Constitution and the overall interest of
the country and the fundamental interest of the people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Persevering efforts were made to integrate legislative work
with major decisions on the country's reform and development, and
conscientiously study and draw on the good experience of
legislation in other countries on the basis of China's realities.
</P>
<P>
Adequate importance should be attached to the mass line in
legislative work and the initiative of various aspects aroused,
and attention and support should be given to local legislation.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he noted, there exist some weak points and
problems in legislation work despite remarkable achievements
scored. Some major laws concerning the market economy have not yet
been worked out, and some existing laws are not complete, whereas
some other laws, with relatively general terms, are not easy to
operate. The power of legislation should further be defined and
law-making procedures have still to be further improved, Tian
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
