<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Commended For Not Devaluing Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- China has made great contributions
to economic and social stability in Asia by deciding not to
devalue its currency amid the current financial crisis in the
region, said economists at the Asian Development Forum here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference by a group of economists, Robert Lawrence
of Harvard University said China is very responsible in the face
of a currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Although devaluation of currencies in other East Asian
countries has exerted great pressures on its exports, China
promised not to devalue its currency in order to maintain regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
If China devalued its currency, the regional crisis would get
even worse, Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
He said China's earnest attitude toward the crisis was also
reflected in its commitment to reforms in the country's banking
system and state-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Other economists also said that as an economic power in Asia,
China's attitude toward the crisis has contributed to economic and
social stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Asked when the Asian financial crisis will end, Vinod Thomas,
director of the Economic Development Institute of the World Bank,
said the history of the past financial crises in Asia and other
regions shows that a financial crisis is unlikely to end too soon.
</P>
<P>
"It depends on what decisive measures will be taken by
individual countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The economists are attending a week-long Asian Development
Forum, which brings together 350 economists, journalists and
government officials to discuss East Asia's development priorities
and needed policy reforms after the outbreak of the financial
crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
