<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Airlines to Buy More Boeing Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Xinjiang Airlines, one of China's
regional carriers based in the country's central Asian region of
the same name, plans to buy 11 Boeing passenger aircraft in the
next three years at a cost of 5.3 billion yuan, Zhang Ruipu,
general manager of the company, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who is in Beijing for the annual session of the
country's top legislature, the National People's Congress (NPC),
also said that Xinjiang, an autonomous region in China's remote
northwest, is expected to complete some airport expansion projects
at a cost of 1.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Government-led investment in infrastructure development to
drive economic growth in underdeveloped areas has been a
successful practice internationally," he said.
</P>
<P>
Construction of infrastructure projects is not limited to
Xinjiang. To promote economic development, the central government
plans to invest a total of 800 billion yuan in resources
development projects in the country's central and western regions
during the period of 1996-2000. Key projects in these regions
total 2,000 in number, 43 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Besides government funding, above 60 percent of loans China
gets from foreign governments and international institutions is
being used in these regions, and 80 percent of them are
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
In Henan, China's most populous province, up to one million kw
of power generating capacity, 100 kilometers of expressways and
100 km of newly-built railways will be put into use annually in
the next few years, according to deputy Li Chengyu from the
province.
</P>
<P>
"If Henan can maintain such a growth momentum, the province
will have improved its infrastructure markedly. The province can
then direct its investment focus to new and high-tech sectors," Li
said.
</P>
<P>
Abudul'ahat Abudurixit, also an NPC deputy and chairman of
Xinjiang Ugyur Autonomous Region, said the region, which makes up
one sixth of China's total land area, has spent a total of 170
billion yuan in capital construction over the recent five years,
up 220 percent over the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
"Infrastructure development is a precondition for ethnic
minority areas to turn their abundant resources into economic
advantages, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
