<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Parliament Fails to Pass Law on Abandoned Flats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Parliament has failed
to pass a bill designed to invalidate wartime decisions on
abandoned houses in the Croat-Muslim Federation.
</P>
<P>
The handling of abandoned houses is one of the biggest
obstacles to an earlier return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to a Sarajevo declaration on the return of refugees,
adopted earlier in February, the wartime law on abandoned flats
was to become invalid at the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
Both houses of the Bosnian parliament met Monday to discuss the
bill proposed by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, all pre-war tenancy holders who abandoned their
homes during the war would be guaranteed the right to regain
them. Those who subsequently moved into these houses should be
provided with alternative accommodation.
</P>
<P>
The representative of the Party of Democratic Action, Semiha
Borovac, also proposed an amendment under which wartime decisions
on the allocation of abandoned flats would not be automatically
proclaimed invalid but "could be rescinded at the party's request."
</P>
<P>
The proposal was supported by her party at the House of
Representatives, but the Croatian representatives voted against it.
</P>
<P>
The federal parliament's House of Peoples adopted the law in
its initial form, as put forward by the federal government,
without the amendment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
