<HEADLINE> Indonesia's MPR Endorses State Policy Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) has endorsed the 1998/2003 State Policy Guidelines,
the blueprint for national development over the next five years,
sources at the MPR said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The MPR approved the Guidelines last night at its plenary
session attended by five factions in the highest legislative
body, said the sources at the sidelines of Tuesday's session
during which President Soeharto was re-elected to his seventh term
of office.
</P>
<P>
When presenting their final views at Tuesday's session,
government factions in the Assembly -- ruling Golkar party, the
Armed Forces and regional representatives -- approved the
guidelines with optimistic comments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minority Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) and
the United Development Party (PPP) cautioned the next government
about bumpy roads ahead because of the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The State Policy Guidelines, which consist of six chapters,
cover a wide range of issues for the next government to address in
the coming five-year term starting next month.
</P>
<P>
Like the 1993/98 Guidelines, the new ones still put emphasis on
the economy as the prime mover of the development. The Assembly
requires the government to implement the policies with improved
efficiency and greater public participation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1968, President Soeharto's New Order government (compared
with Soekarno government) have worked around five-year national
development plans, known as Repelita. The government also run
25-year long-term development plans.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the long-term plans are to bring Indonesia
toward a prosperous, just and self-sufficient society.
</P>
<P>
The MPR General Session, which started on March 1, will end on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis Advances to Evert Cup Tennis Quarter-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- World top-ranked player Martina
Hingis of Sqitzerland swept past Meike Babel of Germany Monday
night, advancing to the quarter-finals of the 1.25 million
U.S. dollars Evert Cup tennis tournament held at Indian Wells,
California.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, making her first appearance in the event, used just 51
minutes to dispose of Babel, 6-2, 6-0. She is to face Anna
Kournikova of Russia or Chanda Rubin of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Swiss girl, who displaced Graf as the No. one
player in the world last March, captured this year's Australian
Open, her fourth Grand Slam title in two years. But she has not
advanced to the finals of any event since losing to world No. 2
Lindsay Davenport in the Pan Pacific Open in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, 12-2 this season, finished 1997 with 12 singles titles.
</P>
<P>
Former No. one Steffi Graf of Germany, the third seed and a
two-time champion at the Evert Cup, continued her return from knee
surgery when she faced No. 11 Ai Sugiyama of Japan in a
third-round match.
</P>
<P>
Graf, the 1994 and 1996 champion, is playing in just her second
tournament and fourth match since undergoing season-ending knee
surgery. After several setbacks in her comeback attempt this
season, she finally made her debut at last month's Faber Grand
Prix in Germany, losing to Sabine Appelmans in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, No. 15 Natasha Zvereva of Belaru ousted sixth
seed Irina Spirlea of Romania by 6-3, 7-5. And unseeded American
Sandra Cacic upset ninth seed Sandrine Testud of France by 4-6,
7-6 (7-3), 7-6 (7-3). 
</P>
</TEXT>
