<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vegetable Prices Soar in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Vegetable prices in New
Zealand have soared in recent days, prompting complaints from
customers and supermarkets alike, the Wellington newspaper The
Evening Post reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said prices for such common vegetables like lettuce,
cauliflower, broccoli and cabbage have doubled or even tripled
those last year.
</P>
<P>
Customers are complaining about the prices and supermarkets
have to put up notices apologizing for the higher prices.
</P>
<P>
Supermarkets said they are losing money despite the high
prices. For instance, one cauliflower is selling for 3.99 New
Zealand dollars (2.3 U.S. dollars), but its cost for the
supermarket itself stands at 4.2 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino phenomenon is being blamed for the price rises with
hot wet weather in prime growing areas causing vegetables to rot
in the ground.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that three months will be needed for bringing
the supply back to normal as a planting cycle usually takes that
long. 
</P>
</TEXT>
