<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Bank Eases Rules on Lending to Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand has proposed
to relax restrictions for Bangkok International Banking Facilities
(BIBF) to increase cash available to local exporters, the Bangkok
Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the country's efforts to boost export, which is
crucial for economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
According to central bank governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi,
regulators are to make three changes in BIBF operations.
</P>
<P>
First, the central bank will reduce the minimum loan through
BIBF to exporters from 2 million U.S. dollars to 500,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The change is effective for borrowers who generate more than
half their revenue from exports. Those who generate more than half
their revenue through product sales or services to exporters are
also involved.
</P>
<P>
Second, BIBF will be allowed to buy unrestricted amount of
foreign currency-denominated export bills from local firms.
</P>
<P>
Previously, BIBF were allowed to buy letters of credit at
discount only from overseas sources, excluding importers and
exporters of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Third, BIBF are to be allowed to guarantee foreign-currency
debt, including letters of credit, for local clients borrowing
from Thai commercial banks or overseas institutions.
</P>
<P>
Local bankers are said to welcome these changes, saying they
would ease liquidity pressures in the economy and boost foreign
capital in the system.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is still waiting for the approval by Finance
Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
