<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Endorses Bills for "Big Bang" Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government approved
four financial system reform bills on Tuesday, including those
designed to implement the "Big Bang" sweeping deregulation of
financial markets in the country.
</P>
<P>
The bills were formulated by the Finance Ministry in line with
proposals put forward last June by the Securities and Exchange
Council and two other advisory panels on financial issues,
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
They feature liberalization of brokerage commissions, changes
to the current licensing system to a register-based one for new
entrants to the securities business, and abolishing barriers
between the banking, brokerage and insurance businesses by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Of the four bills, two are aimed at promoting special-purpose
companies to scrutinize property-backed bad loans owed by Japanese
banks.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to submit the bills to the Diet
(parliament) by the end of this week so they can be enacted by the
end of the current regular Diet session in June, the officials
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
