<HEADLINE> IFC Launches South African Rand Global Notes Offering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) announced on Monday the launching of a South
African rand 200 million bond issue which is about 40.3 million
U.S. dollars under its Global Medium-Term Note program.
</P>
<P>
The 2-year Step-Down notes carry an issue price of 100.875
percent and an annual coupon of 16.25 percent per annum in the
first year and of 9.50 percent per annum in the second year.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds of the issue will be swapped into U.S. dollar
floating rate funds for IFC.
</P>
<P>
The lead manager is ABN Amro Bank NV with Caboto and Toronto
Dominion Bank as co-lead managers. An additional five financial
institutions completed the syndicate group.
</P>
<P>
The latest transaction brings IFC's market borrowing to about
3,400 million dollars for the fiscal year 1998, which began on
July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and also the largest
multilateral source of financing for private sector projects in
developing countries. 
</P>
