<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Supreme Court Declines to Take up Affirmative Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Supreme Court,
increasingly skeptical of efforts to give minorities special help
without proof of discrimination, on Monday refused to revive a
Florida county's affirmative-action program for awarding
construction contracts.
</P>
<P>
The court turned down Dade County's argument that
discrimination in the local construction industry is severe enough
to justify an effort to aid black-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The court also declined to hear an appeal by a minority
contractors' group that sought to reinstate portions of similar
programs in Dade County for companies owned by Hispanics and women.
</P>
<P>
The affirmative action is a formal effort to provide employment
and education opportunities for women and ethnic minorities to
overcome past patterns of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The justice has strictly limited programs of affirmative action
in state and local public works projects since 1989, saying such
efforts must be narrowly tailored to remedy the effects of past
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
"We know there is discrimination and that it's unfortunately
alive and well," said Thomas F. Pepe, a lawyer who represents the
Allied Minority Contractors Association. "It's just that it's very
difficult to prove discrimination."
</P>
<P>
With the proper research on the continuing effects of
discrimination, it is possible to win court decisions upholding
affirmative action programs, Pepe said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Supreme Court said federal programs that aim to
help minorities must meet the same strict standard required of
state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
The high court also has restricted the use of racial
considerations in drawing election districts, while lower courts
have cut back on affirmative action in public university admission
policies.
</P>
<P>
In another affirmative-action case Monday, the court rejected
an appeal of a former Nevada college professor who said she was
discriminated because she is white. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0263 </DOCNO>
