<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Re-elected Indonesia's President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Soeharto was re-elected President
of Indonesia on Tuesday for a fresh five-year term, making the
retired general one of the longest-serving heads of state in the
world.
</P>
<P>
His re-election, a foregone conclusion, was agreed upon by the
1,000-member People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) without taking a
poll.
</P>
<P>
"Since there was only one presidential candidate, he is
automatically formalized as president according to the law,"
Chairman of the Assembly Harmoko said at the 10th plenary session
of the MPR.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest legislative body which started
its general session on March 1 will end on Wednesday after
endorsing the State Policy guideline for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto's re-election was assured early last month when the
main political groups, including the ruling Golkar party and the
powerful military, gave him their supports.
</P>
<P>
Since he came to power in 1967, Soeharto has stood unopposed in
all seven elections in the giant Southeast Asian country with a
population of 202 million.
</P>
<P>
The re-election is the climax of the Assembly which consisted
of elected parliamentarians and a slightly greater number of
appointed members.
</P>
<P>
The president will take his oath of office at the Assembly on
Wednesday after which representatives will elect and swear in the
vice president.
</P>
<P>
The election of the vice president will be held on Wednesday
before the conclusion of the Assembly meeting that day .
</P>
<P>
All five assembly factions -- the Armed Forces, the ruling
Golkar Party, the United Development Party (PPP), the Indonesian
Democratic party (PDI) and regional representatives -- have named
State Minister of Research and Technology Yusuf Habibie as the
sole candidate for the vice presidency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
