<P>
Xiang Jianhai, deputy director of the Marine Research Institute
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said nine research projects
related to marine science and technology have been included into
China's national program for scientific and technological
development from 1996 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The projects, which cover ocean environment monitoring,
offshore oil and gas exploitation and comprehensive use of marine
resources, have a total investment of approximately one billion
yuan," said Xiang, who is also a deputy to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature in session here
since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his institute is expected to receive 50 million
yuan in research funds this year alone, while the country totally
spent less than 100 million yuan on marine science and technology
in the previous five-year period from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
"With a growing pressure from population, resources and the
environment, the mankind has been increasingly compelled to seek
economic growth from the oceans, and the next century will witness
a comprehensive development of marine resources by humans," the
oceanologist predicted.
</P>
<P>
China has a coastline of more than 18,000 km and three million
sq km of sea territories, or one third of its land space.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that by 2050, the population in China's
coastal areas will surge to 50 percent of the country's total from
the current 40 percent, with at least 800 million people.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since the early 1990s, marine economy in
China has maintained an average annual growth rate of about 22
percent, doubling the average growth rate of China's gross
domestic product in the past five years. In 1996, the total output
value of China's marine economy reached 285 billion yuan (35
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, Xiang acknowledged that China still lags far behind
the developed countries in terms of marine science and technology
and in developing marine resources.
</P>
<P>
At the ongoing session of the Ninth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
several CPPCC members have suggested that the central government
set up a special committee to regulate and promote the country's
marine economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
