<HEADLINE> Thailand Likely to Call For Emergency Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Finance Ministry and the
Bank of Thailand would likely call for emergency aid if the baht
comes under attack, Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said.
</P>
<P>
"The baht riding between 45 and 46 baht per U.S. dollar is
normal. But if the baht slides much lower, we may call for
financial help from the IMF," Tarrin told reporters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said the aid would help strengthen the country's foreign
reserves which currently stand at 26.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The baht on Monday ended lower at 44.50 to the dollar, compared
with 44.40 at the previous close trading.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the baht's weakness to Indonesia's failure
to secure another batch of loans from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Tarrin admitted that the IMF's delay over Indonesia's rescue
loan as well as the ailing banking sector in Malaysia have had a
moderate impact on the baht.
</P>
<P>
But he said he was confident that the support of leaders from
both the United States and Japan would help get investors
confidence back on track soon in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In another development, analysts of U.S.-based international
rating agency Moody's Investors Service on Monday met with Thai
authorities for a review after the agency earlier lowered
Thailand's rating to junk bond status. Moody's rival, Standard and
Poor's, met with the authorities last week, the Nation newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We invite the rating agencies to review Thailand's ratings and
get updated information," Tarrin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
