<HEADLINE> Tamil Rebel's Bomb Kills Five in Eastern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A policeman and four civilians
were killed Monday evening in a bomb blast carried out by rebels
of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) at Eravur, Eastern
Province of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The bomb missed a military convoy it had targeted at, but
devastated the area including several shops and injured two other
policemen and 15 civilians, according to the Island newspaper
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the bomb had been assembled into a tractor by
the LTTE rebels and placed in a motor garage to wait for the
convoy to pass.
</P>
<P>
Although the convoy arrived on time, the blast had no effect on
it but instead blew up the tractor driver and cleaner to pieces.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who are fighting for survival in the north where
government forces have launched a major offensive to clear 75
kilometers of roadway through rebel-held territory, have been
launching attacks in other areas to divert attention from the
north.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 15-year-old war for a separate
state in the country's north and east. The government says more
than 55,000 people have been killed in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Last week a lone LTTE suicide bomber drove his vehicle into
Downtown Colombo, killing 38 people and injuring about 300 others.
</P>
<P>
</P>
