<HEADLINE> Dai Ethnic Charm Lures Tourists to Festival (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Yan Hanpeng, 60, once wondered how
the Water Splashing Festival could lure increasing tourists to
remote Xishuangbanna.
</P>
<P>
"We've celebrated the festival for generations, and it is only
now that it has become a tourist attraction," said Yan, a member
of the Dai ethnic group from Gasa Township.
</P>
<P>
As tourists kept coming, he decided to open a Dai inn, which
has become a booming business.
</P>
<P>
Through more direct contacts with his guests, he has a better
understanding of tourists and their interest in the Dai folklore.
</P>
<P>
"They are obsessed with every bit of our life, from the unique
festivals and bamboo houses, to the colorful costumes and food,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Xishuangbanna in southwest China's Yunnan Province is China's
only autonomous prefecture of the Dai ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 1.8 million tourists across China and the
world visited Xishuangbanna, which is also known for its vast
tracts of untouched tropical rainforests, where herds of wild
elephants live.
</P>
<P>
The Water Splashing Festival, which is held around March 12, is
a highlight for tourism. According to the Dai tradition, people during
the festival put on their best clothes and splash water on each
other to extend their best wishes. During the festival, there are
usually a dozen fully loaded daily flights bringing tourists from
Kunming, the provincial capital, to Jinghong, the prefectural
capital. Hotel rooms are so full that tourists have to make
reservations early.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dai Ethnic Charm Lures Tourists to Festival (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xishuangbanna tourist authorities have opened several Dai
villages to tourists. Climbing up the steps, guests enter a
suspended bamboo house where they see how traditional and modern
ways of life are intertwined.
</P>
<P>
Travelers can also take a walk in the village where they can
appreciate Dai dancing and singing, and buy local products in
village shops.
</P>
<P>
The Dai people are devout Buddhists and all Dai boys become monks
at the age of 7 or 8. In almost every village there is a Buddhist
temple, which also draws tourists.
</P>
<P>
Despite their cultural and tourist value, some Dai villages
have been destroyed to pave the way for modern construction. In an
effort to preserve the Dai culture and architecture, and to
develop tourism, the provincial government has designated a number
of Dai villages to retain the original layouts and architectural
style forever.
</P>
<P>
The government has also worked out rules governing the
preservation of forests and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
"With so many people interested in and taking care of our
culture and the living environment, we feel closer to the world,"
Yan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
