<HEADLINE> Canada's Hydropower Project on Churchill Gets Go-ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Quebec and Newfoundland announced
Monday that they have agreed to start formal negotiations on a new
hydroelectric project on Churchill River in Labrador.
</P>
<P>
The 10-billion-dollar (700 million U.S. dollars) deal was made
public when Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard met his Newfoundland
counterpart Brian Tobin in Churchill Falls, Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
The two Canadian provinces have agreed in principle to build a
2,200-megawatt power station at Gull Island and add a
1,000-megawatt new plant at the existing Churchill Falls dam.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed deal, Newfoundland and Labrador Hydro would hold
a 66-percent ownership in the joint ventures, while Hydro Quebec will
have 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Having agreed on this framework, officials can now focus on the
task of concluding agreements that will result in significant benefits
for both Newfoundland and Labrador and Quebec," Premier Tobin said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
"These projects will strengthen the position of Hydro Quebec as a
North American leader in the energy sector," said Premier Bouchard.
</P>
<P>
"These agreements will allow both our governments to create
significant economic development," Bouchard added.
</P>
<P>
Monday's initial agreements are expected to lead to a final deal
by the end of this year. 
</P>
