<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Indonesian President Soeharto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
Tuesday was re-elected to a seventh five-year term (1998-2003).
Here is a profile of the president.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was born in a farmer family in the densely-populated
Central Java on June 8, 1921. His father was a village staff in
charge of water distribution service.
</P>
<P>
"I am not a royal offspring. I am the son of Kertosudiro, a
village staff responsible for water distribution service with no
piece of land at all," Soeharto said in his biography.
</P>
<P>
He only received formal education at a junior high school, but
later with the military training and education, he won his laurels
and obtained the highest military and civilian positions.
</P>
<P>
Starting as a non-commissioned officer in the Dutch colonial
army and a member of the Indonesian militia during the Japanese
occupation, Soeharto was promoted to the country's military
leadership when he distinguished himself during the fight for
independence in the second half of the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was regimental commander, brigadier general and major
general from 1945 to 1962. From 1970 to 1965, he worked as deputy
chief of army staff and then as chief of army staff between 1965
and 1968.
</P>
<P>
He became acting president in 1967 to replace Indonesia's
founding president Soekarno. Then he became president in 1968. He
has since run unopposed and elected by acclamation for six times.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was Known as the "father of development" in Indonesia.
Under his leadership, Indonesia's per capita gross domestic
product jumped from a mere 60 U.S. dollars in 1966 when he came
into power to the current more than 1,000 dollars. Indonesia, the
formerly world's largest rice importer, became self-sufficient in
the crop in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Soeharto also drove Indonesia's economy away from a
dependency on oil and gas export earnings by boosting exports of
manufactured products, textiles and wood products.
</P>
<P>
At present, Soeharto is leading his country to cope with the
monetary crisis that started in July last year and hit other
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto has played an important role in international affairs,
especially in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
and the Non-Aligned Movement. He supports the South-South
cooperation and the establishment of a new political and economic
order in the world.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, 76, has three sons and three daughters who have
already given him a number of grandchildren. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Italy's Efforts in Joining Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Finance and economy ministers from
the European Union endorsed Italy's admission to the single
currency after hearing Rome's plans to cut its national debt and
budget deficit on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government plans to reduce the budget deficit to
1.2 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) by 2001 and cut the
national debt to 100 percent in six years, Italy's Treasury and
Budget Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi said at a meeting of EU
ministers in Brussels today.
</P>
<P>
Though skeptical of Rome's resolve to slash deficit and debt
figures in the future, Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm
expressed satisfaction with Ciampi's plans.
</P>
<P>
"Just on the basis of 1997 accounts one could have many doubts
about the sustainability of Italy's efforts," he said. "But today
Ciampi illustrated to us a plan that goes up to 2001."
</P>
<P>
He said he was sure Italy's budget deficit and national debt
would continue to fall.
</P>
<P>
"The plan has the support of parliament, and this is a crucial
point because it means that budgetary rigor will carry on in
coming years," Zalm added.
</P>
<P>
Italy also gained some support from its EU partners to reduce
its national debt, which at 121 percent of GDP is twice the 60
percent criterion for participating the economic and monetary
union.
</P>
<P>
The European Monetary Institute will urge countries with high
national debt, namely Belgium and Italy, to cut the rate to 60
percent in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, Ciampi has unveiled a plan to reduce the rate to
the required level within 12 to 18 years.
</P>
<P>
"All countries with excessive national debt need to reduce it,"
said French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn. "But we can't
impose a deadline." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
