<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-UNDP Project to Disinfect Stored Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- A sino-UNDP project launched
earlier this years is protecting stored grain from pests through
advanced radiation technology in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will invest a total of 1.3 million US
dollars in this project while receiving 452,000 US dollars in
grant assistance from the United Nations Development Program to
demonstrate reusable and clean methods of ridding warehouses of
agricultural pests.
</P>
<P>
The project will be carried out in Beijing and Fangcheng port
in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, an important grain
transfer station.
</P>
<P>
Qinghua Science Park, affiliated with Qinghua University, and
Fangcheng Harbour Administration are the implementing agencies.
</P>
<P>
A rough estimate puts China's post-harvest grain losses at 92
million tons per year, nearly 20 percent of the gross grain output
of the country.
</P>
<P>
About a quarter of that, or 23 million tons worth five billion
US dollars was lost to insect infestation.
</P>
<P>
The country's current methods of chemical fumigation are not
only expensive and unsafe but also environment hazardous.
</P>
<P>
Radiation technology can decrease and eventually eliminate the
use of chemicals in grain disinfestation, helping to protect the
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
