<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, March 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA -- Currencies in Latin American and East European
countries in the fourth quarter of 1997 were little affected by
the Asia economic crisis, a bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Basle-based Bank for International Settlements (BIS) also
said that equity indices in North America and Europe rapidly
recouped their losses.
</P>
<P>
The risk premium on Latin American and Eastern European
countries' foreign currency securities quickly retreated from
their late October peak, according to the BIS.
</P>
<P>
The subdued pace of securities issues in the second half of the
quarter reflected borrowers' willingness to delay issue in
anticipation of improved conditions as much as outright rationing
by international investors, the BIS
said. (Switzerland-BIS-Currencies)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Visiting Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani on Monday
urged neighboring Greece to help defuse the growing tension in
Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The tension in Kosovo would pose "a serious threat" to peace in
the Balkan region, Mejdani said after meeting his Greek
counterpart, Costis Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
He added that Greece, as a member of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU), should play its
role in helping to seek a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mejdani, who arrived here Monday for three days, was on his
first official visit to Greece. (Greece-Albania-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano on Monday promised
to pacify national extremism in the country and to propose a
solution to the Kosovo issue acceptable to all parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Nano made the remark after British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
briefed him by telephone on the results of a meeting of the
Contact Group on Bosnia held in London on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the member countries of the Contact Group
met in London to discuss the growing ethnic tensions in Kosovo, a
province of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. Ethnic Albanians
make up 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic conflicts in Kosovo have led to the killing of four
policemen and 16 ethnic Albanians since February
28. (Albania-UK-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- Ukraine reserved the right to ask neighboring
countries to eliminate nuclear weapons, visiting Ukrainian Defense
Minister Oleksandr Kuzmuk said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine was the first state in the world to voluntarily get
rid of its nuclear weapons and it feels it has the right to ask
neighboring countries to do the same," Kuzmuk said during a visit
to Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the Ukrainian stance on Hungary joining the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), Kuzmuk said his country
respected all other nations' sovereignty and their right to choose
their own partners.
</P>
<P>
The strategic goal of Ukraine was to join European integration
and become part of a new European defence system, he
said. (Ukraine-Hungary-Nuclear)
</P>
