<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Eximbank Funding Two Ventures in Cameroon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- The Export and Import Bank of
China (Eximbank) has signed two Chinese government concessional
loan agreements with the Cameroon National Investment Corp,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Bank sources have reported that the loans, worth tens of
millions of yuan, will be used to establish two joint ventures in
Cameroon: a tyre renovation factory and a tractor assembly plant.
</P>
<P>
China's Gansu Tyre Factory and Wuhan Tractor Plant will be
involved in the two projects which will create job opportunities
for Cameroon and help the development of that country's rubber
industry, agricultural machinery and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The projects will help promote China's export of machinery
equipment and technology, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese government concessional loans are now a major part of
China's foreign aid program since China decided in 1995 that it
would no longer provide interest-free loans to other counties. It
aims to expand the scale of China's foreign aid to help developing
countries promote their economic growth and fortify Sino-foreign
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
By the end of February, the Eximbank had provided such loans on
nearly 30 projects in such fields as oil exploration, forestry,
gold mining, fish processing, automobile assembly and railway
upgrading. The loans mainly go to the developing countries, like
Sudan, Cote d'Ivoire, Gabon, Papua New Guinea and Guyana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
