<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania to Propose Solution to Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano
on Monday promised to pacify national extremism in the country and
to propose a solution to the Kosovo issue acceptable to all
parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Nano made the remark after British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
briefed him by telephone on the results of a meeting of the
Contact Group on Bosnia held in London on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the member countries of the Contact Group
met in London to discuss the growing ethnic tensions in Kosovo, a
province of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. Ethnic Albanians
make up 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic conflicts in Kosovo have led to the killing of four
policemen and 16 ethnic Albanians since February 28.
</P>
<P>
Appreciating the Contact Group's position, which is not to
treat "the Kosovo issue as a domestic issue of Yugoslavia," Nano
told Cook that his government will continue to control the border
(with Yugoslavia) and try its best to pacify the growing national
extremism in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said Albania will continue to be an active partner of the
Contact Group in dealing with the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Cook said the Contact Group will keep in touch with
Yugoslavia's neighboring countries, including Albania and
Macedonia. He will also visit the two countries this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
