<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investments Decline in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Foreign equity investments
registered with the Philippine Central Bank dropped 17.8 percent
to 1.053 billion U.S. dollars last year from 1.281 billion dollars
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The drop was indicative of the foreign investors' skittishness,
an aftermath of the regional currency crisis, the Business World
Tuesday quoted central bank director for economic research Diwa
Guinigundo as saying.
</P>
<P>
Guinigundo said the July 11 de facto devaluation of the peso
last year resulted in the outflow of dollars as foreign fund
managers began repatriating their investments.
</P>
<P>
"In the first nine months of last year, we already saw
portfolio investments and direct investments go down," he said.
</P>
<P>
The largest drop in registered investments was seen in the
manufacturing sector which contracted 65 percent to 172.19 million
dollars from 477.69 million dollars in 1996, the latest data from
the central bank showed.
</P>
<P>
Investments in banks and other financial institutions fell 56
percent to 226.36 million dollars from 513.26 million dollars.
Investments in banks, in particular, showed a drop of 67 percent
to 112.6 million dollars from 342.98 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
An increase was only exhibited in investments for the
construction and public utilities sectors.
</P>
<P>
Investments in the construction sector, composed of transport
facilities, infrastructure, building and general engineering, rose
to 242.75 million dollars from just 45.36 million dollars the
previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
