<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Booming at Port on China-Vietnam Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- Hekou County on the
Sino-Vietnamese border, formerly a marshland, has grown into a
boomtown since the state approved a port there in 1992 as part of
the nationwide effort to open wider to the outside.
</P>
<P>
Le Kien Hong, a Vietnamese businessman, buys several hundred
tons of potatoes in Hekou every month, before he moves them back to
his home country through the port.
</P>
<P>
"People in my country like potatoes very much, but we don't
have enough," Le said. "That's why I have chosen the potato
business. And what's more, China's potatoes are of high quality
and at low prices."
</P>
<P>
The county faces the Vietnamese town of Lai Cao across the Nanxi
River, straddled by a 200-meter bridge which enables trains,
vehicles and pedestrians to pass. The city proper now has smooth
roads, new buildings and crowds of people.
</P>
<P>
Every day, several thousand traders come and go through the
port. The county had more than 700 million yuan in imports and
exports in 1997 -- 18 times that of 1989, 600 Vietnamese-funded
warehouses, and 180 border trade businesses opened by
Chinese provinces, according to local statistics.
</P>
<P>
Hekou has a population of 80,000, but it now receives more than
3,000 tourists from at home and abroad daily. It has built 33
hotels with 2,700 beds and telephone service accessible to 120
countries and regions, said the county's deputy magistrate, Long
Shiqiu.
</P>
<P>
"It's no more than 300 kilometers to go by train from Hekou to
Hanoi, capital of Vietnam. So farm produce and agricultural
byproducts, and metals like tin and copper in southwest China, are
being shipped overseas, while cotton yarn, gasoline, and
cigarettes are moving into China," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
