<HEADLINE> Chinese Island Province Getting More Investment from Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 10 (Xinhua) -- In 1997, over 50 Taiwanese-funded
companies were set up in Hainan, China's southernmost province.
</P>
<P>
Economic exchanges and cooperation between the two island
provinces of China continued to increase in spite of the financial
turmoil in Asia, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Taiwanese investors have mainly focused on small businesses,
80 percent of them have less than 500,000 US dollars worth of
capital.
</P>
<P>
Their investments changed after 1994, from the real estate
sector to farming. Hainan now has over 250 farms with nearly 200
million US dollars worth of funding from Taiwan, most of them
fruit plantations. 
</P>
