<HEADLINE> Canada Announces Sanctions Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government announced
Monday several sanctions against Yugoslavia for its alleged
violence against ethnic Albanians in its province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy announced the unilateral
measures in the House of Commons, which include suspending
Canadian export credits to Yugoslavia and negotiations over
Canadian landing rights for Yugoslavian aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Canada will also suspend all bilateral discussions and consider
humanitarian aid to the affected population, said reports Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is quite clear that the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia government must understand the repressive actions taken
will not be tolerated by the international community," Axworthy
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday in London, representatives from the United
States, Britain and other Western countries agreed on new
sanctions against Yugoslavia. Canada did not attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy said that he will discuss the decisions out of the
London meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Albright will arrive here late Monday for a two-day visit to
Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
