<HEADLINE> Canada's Housing Starts Up in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's housing starts went up in
February after a slowdown in the previous month, said reports
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The country's residential construction bounced back 11 percent
to 157,200 in February on a projected annual basis in January,
when the great ice storm in central and eastern Canada slowed down
housing activity.
</P>
<P>
Single-detached housing starts in urban areas went up 9.6
percent in the month to 80,700 units on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, multiple starts rose 18.6 percent to 54,300,
according to statistics from Canada Mortgage and Housing Corp.
</P>
<P>
The Febraury figure "stands among the best since 1994 and
prospects for housing remain very positive," a CMHC economist was
quoted as saying. 
</P>
