<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Reaffirms Passive Smoking Causes Lung Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
reaffirmed here Monday that passive smoking causes lung cancer in
non-smokers.
</P>
<P>
WHO made the statement at a time when the organization was, in
recent news reports, accused of suppressing information and having
withheld from publication its own report of a study which
supposedly failed to scientifically prove that there is an
association between passive smoking and a number of diseases, lung
cancer in particular.
</P>
<P>
The results of this study, WHO stressed, are very much in line
with the results of similar studies both in Europe and elsewhere:
passive smoking does cause lung cancer in non-smokers.
</P>
<P>
WHO said that the study found that there was an estimated 16
percent increased risk of lung cancer among non-smoking spouses of
smokers. For workplace exposure the estimated increase in risk was
17 percent.
</P>
<P>
In February 1998, WHO recalled, according to usual scientific
practice, a paper reporting the main study results was sent to a
reputable scientific journal for consideration and review.
</P>
<P>
That is why the full report is not yet publicly available, WHO
said. Under the circumstances, however, the authors of the study
have agreed to make an abstract of the report available to the
media.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely important to note that the results of this
study are consistent with the results of major scientific reviews
of this question published during 1997 by the government of
Australia, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and the State
of California," said Neil Collishaw, acting chief of WHO's Tobacco
or Health Unit in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"A major meta-analysis of passive smoking and lung cancer was
also published in the British Medical Journal in 1997," Collishaw
said. "From these and other previous reviews of the scientific
evidence emerges a clear global scientific consensus, passive
smoking does cause lung cancer and other diseases."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says It may Consult U.N. Before Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Monday
that it may consult with the other members of the U.N. Security
Council before any military action against Iraq if it failed to
abide by its agreement on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"If we got to the point where there were serious questions
about the government of Iraq's willingness to honor the memorandum
of understanding, we would of course be consulting with members of
the Security Council," White House spokesman Mike McCurry told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I would expect urgent deliberations to occur if there was any
abrogation of the agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on remarks by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan who said Sunday that he believed the United States was
"required" to consult with the United Nations before resorting to
any military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"If the U.S. had to strike, I think some sort of consultations
with the other members would be required," Annan told the ABC TV
program "This Week" Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But the United States has repeatedly said it believes it
already has the authority to launch a military strike if Iraq
violates the agreement it struck with Annan last month to allow
U.N. weapons inspectors into sensitive Iraqi sites.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the United States has from previous U.N.
resolutions adequate authority to take air strike on Iraq, McCurry
said, "That is exactly our position."
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, McCurry said the United States had "a
different view" on "consultations" that Annan believed were
necessary before any U.S. military action.
</P>
<P>
But McCurry said he had made the earlier remarks because he
"wasn't completedly familiar with the secretary-general's
remarks."
</P>
<P>
He believed what Annan had said "simply that he expected the
United States would consult further in the event that there was
need to take additional action there if there were abrogation of
the agreement of understanding between the United Nations and
Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Asked what the White House would do if it met resistance to
using force during consultations, McCurry said, "We have had very
high-level consultations with all the members of the Security
Council."
</P>
<P>
"If there were an abrogation of this current memorandum of
understanding by the government of Iraq, our judgment is: the
disposition regarding use of force would be much
</P>
</TEXT>
