<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-09 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Tells Israel: Not to Play Tricks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Monday called on the Israeli government not to play "tricky games"
on the Mideast peace, saying only building trust will help break
the deadlock, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Israeli Maariv newspaper, the Egyptian
leader said the ball is now in the Israeli court concerning the
long-stalled Arab-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
If Israeli leaders really want to solve the problem of South
Lebanon as they have said, then they should solve the Palestinian
problem and build trust with Syrians first, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks which started in 1991 were put on hold
after a string of suicide bombings hit Israel in early 1996. The
negotiations between Palestinians and Israelis have been stalled
for a year due to Israeli settlement buildings in occupied Arab
lands and delayed Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"The Syrians see what is happening with the Palestinians and
have no faith in you," Mubarak said, calling upon the Israelis to
implement all the deals signed with the Palestinians without
manoeuvering.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president did not deny the lukewarmness plaguing
Egyptian-Israeli relations, explaining that some professional
associations have a tough stand against cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The public opinion (in Egypt) is excited," said the president,
blaming this on Israel.
</P>
<P>
In the Monday interview, Mubarak refused to suggest a certain
percentage for Israeli redeployment in the West Bank, saying that
the size of withdrawal should be reasonable to the satisfaction of
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"If you want to ensure the security of Israel you should show
the necessary flexibility," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he cannot tell Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat the kind of redeployment or size of
withdrawal he should accept, otherwise the Egyptian side may be
blamed by the Palestinians for what consequences might ensue.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who frequently visits Egypt and consults Mubarak, calls
for Israeli withdrawal from 90 percent of the West Bank. The
Israeli government has not come up with a final proposal, but
analysts said 40-50 percent withdrawal would be the most that
could be offered.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to have peace treaty with
Israel, in 1979, but ties have remained cool. The relations
plummeted after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took
power in May 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
