<HEADLINE> U.N. Arms Inspection in Iraq Goes on Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Nine U.N. arms inspection teams
visited 13 sites Monday in Iraq, and these visits were made with
full cooperation from the Iraqi side, an Iraqi government
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for Iraqi National Monitoring Department, the
Iraqi peer of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarmament
in Iraq, said that of all sites visited by the arms inspectors
Monday, three sites are not under monitoring.
</P>
<P>
He said that the inspection team led by American Scott Ritter
carried out its inspection from Sunday morning until early Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. office in Baghdad refused to comment on the news that
Ritter's team visited accessory buildings of presidential
palaces.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed on February 23 by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz, inspections of presidential sites should be carried
out by UNSCOM inspectors with the presence of senior diplomats
appointed by Annan.
</P>
<P>
In mid-January, a 16-member arms inspection team led by Ritter
was barred from carrying out its activities by the Iraqi
government on the ground that its composition was imbalanced. That
team included nine Americans and Five Britons.
</P>
<P>
A new 50-member team led by Ritter returned to Baghdad last
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
