<DOCNO> XIE19980310.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-09 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Israel Boost Trade Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordan, one of the two Arab
countries having peace treaty with Israel, signed several trade
agreements with the Jewish country here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed at a press conference after a
meeting between King Hussein of Jordan and visiting Israeli
Minister of Industry and Trade Natahn Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky and his Jordanian counterpart Hani Mulqi signed a
mutual recognition document regarding the Irbid Qualified
Industrial Zone (QIZ) in northern Jordan. Exports from the zone to
the United States are entitled to be duty-free.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the two ministers signed an agreement on establishing
an Israeli laboratory in Amman to examine Jordanian goods to
ensure they comply with Israeli specifications.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Mulqi said that he also discussed with
Sharansky the renewal and expansion of a bilateral trade protocol,
which expires in October and grants tariff reduction of up to 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the current talks could boost trade
volume of bilateral trade in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Jordan and Israel was no more than
35 million U.S. dollars in 1997, which was an essential leap over
that of 1996, said Mulqi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jordanian-Israeli joint committee during their
Monday meetings discussed means of developing bilateral trade
relations and facilitating Jordan's trade with the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA), Mulqi added.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, the two sides also signed a joint letter
to request European Union (EU)'s duty exemption for Jordanian and
Israeli exports to EU countries, according to Mulqi.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Jordan signed a trade partnership agreement
with the EU, allowing its products free access to Europe. Israel
has already had such agreement with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky arrived here Monday as part of efforts to restore
bilateral relations strained by Israeli agents' botched
assassination attempt on a Hamas (Islamic Resistance
Movement) leader here last September.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan is
scheduled to visit Tel Aviv on Tuesday in the first trip to
Israel by a member of Jordanian Royal family.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt are the only two Arab countries that
reached peace treaty with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
